<SECOND>AM-Quayle Visit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0813,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Says Exxon Will Be Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The tanker...,' to CORRECT barrels to gallons.
^With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSANNE PAGANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> stopped in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> on Monday and reassured officials that cleanup work is not over on the oil-smeared beaches of Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. `` The job is not complete,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said during a brief refueling stop en route to <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. `` You have our assurance that we will stay until the job is complete.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was referring to the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s role as federal coordinator in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Commandant <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> has been monitoring <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s cleanup work since three weeks after the March 24 wreck of the tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON>. The tanker spilled nearly 11 million gallons of oil into Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> after slamming into a reef, resulting in the nation's worst oil spill Exxon declared its summer cleanup finished on Friday. The company said dwindling sunlight and deteriorating weather made further work this year unsafe. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s visit came as President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> visited the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> in a swing through <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> defended his decision not to travel to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, saying he had sent his `` environmental vice president.'' During his visit, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> spent about a half-hour with <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s `` oiled mayors'' _ the mayors of five coastal communities where crude continues to wash up on shore and where fishing fleets generally were tied up for the summer Last May, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> inspected the oil spill cleanup on <LOCATION> Smith </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said Monday it would not surprise him to learn that parts of the island, among the first and hardest hit by the spill, remain oily months after cleanup began. The <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> mayors apparently won no new promises of action from the administration. But <LOCATION> Kodiak </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodie </PERSON> said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> seemed to listen to the mayors' concerns about the federal cleanup role next spring. `` We told him the spill's not over just because <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> has completed work and gone,'' <PERSON> Brodie </PERSON> said. The vice president also met briefly with driftnet fishermen, who are concerned about the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's new agreement aimed at restricting driftnet fleets from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> from fishing the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> for squid. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fishermen oppose the use of driftnets by foreign fleets because they contend the lightweight nets illegally harvest thousands of tons of salmon and steelhead.
