<HEAD>SWAPO Taken To Court In Dispute Over Missing Detainees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Court proceedings were instituted against the leader of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> by a group seeking information about hundreds of people the guerrilla movement allegedly detained. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON>, who returned last week after 30 years in exile, was served with court papers Monday by a deputy sheriff following the legal move by the <ORGANIZATION> Parents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. The committee alleged that <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> has failed to account for about 1,400 people who were put to work at guerrilla bases in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> during the movement's 23-year bush war against <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African rule in neighboring <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has agreed to grant the territory independence, and <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> is favored to win U.N.-supervised elections in November for an assembly that will draft a constitution. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> contends that it complied with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> independence plan by releasing all prisoners in its custody. But the <ORGANIZATION> Parents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, in documents filed with the territorial <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, claimed 1,400 people either remain in <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> prison camps or have disappeared. The committee called on <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> to account for the whereabouts of the missing people. A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> delegation is due back in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> soon after a trip to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> to determine whether any prisoners are at <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> camps. According to freed detainees, hundreds of <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> members were accused of being South African spies and many were tortured until they signed confessions. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> leaders have confirmed incidents of torture, and have countered that the South African-led security forces also were guilty of brutality.
