<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Incentive     09-19 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Incentive,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pay in Foreign Products Inspires Soviets to Work 10 Times Harder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Berry-pickers in the Soviet Far North gathered ten times as many blueberries and cranberries this year after a Swedish-Soviet firm offered to pay them with foreign fashions and consumer electronics, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> says. The Soviet news agency reported <PERSON> Mondya </PERSON> that cooperatives in the <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION> area gathered 100 tons of blueberries and 500 tons of cowberries, a type of tundra cranberry, for a Swedish-Soviet joint venture called Artikfryuz. That is ten times the amount they collected in their most productive years. Soviet stores are nearly empty, particularly in provincial towns like <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION>. The few goods often are allocated by privilege, so Soviet workers paid in rubles can find themselves with nothing to buy. Soviet citizens are not allowed to hold foreign currency, and the handful who work for foreign firms receive a fraction of their pay in credit at hard currency stores. The Tass story was the first to indicate that foreign firms might be able to pay Soviets directly with imported consumer goods. The Soviet government also has started an experiment that will pay grain farmers in hard currency for producing extra wheat in hopes of cutting the amount they now import at higher, world-market prices.
</TEXT>
