<HEAD>Arizona Senators Face Martin Luther King Day Bill Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Backers of a holiday to honor assassinated civil rights leader <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> are hoping the prospect of a Super Bowl can succeed where convention boycotts and bad publicity failed. `` Without a holiday, there is little chance in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> for a Super Bowl,'' House Minority Leader <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, a Democrat who leads the pro-holiday forces, said Monday. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Shover </PERSON>, a newspaper executive who heads the booster group <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> 93, agreed. `` We feel sure if we do n't have a King holiday we wo n't be on a level playing field for the'93 Super Bowl,'' said <PERSON> Shover </PERSON>, director of community and corporate services for <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, publishers of The <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION>. The issue comes up as part of a special session that begins Wednesday on prison crowding, drugs and economic development, and both sides are squirming already. `` If we fail again, the frustration level ... will rise,'' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said. But Senate President <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Usdane </PERSON>, a Republican who wants the issue referred to a general election ballot, said the bill is not appropriate for a special session. `` With a special session, you want to get out quickly,'' Usdane said. `` You do n't need controversy in a special session.'' The Republican-controlled House has voted for a King holiday in the past, but conservative <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> have defeated the proposal. The fight has been going on for years. Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>, then about to launch a presidential campaign and frustrated by lack of progress on the King issue, signed an executive proclamation in 1986 giving state employees the day off. Republican state Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> declared that <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON> lacked authority to issue such an order, however. <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>'s successor, Republican <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, rescinded the proclamation before it could take effect <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> also said he did not believe that King deserved a holiday, and civil rights groups launched a boycott of the state as a convention site. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s impeachment in April 1988 on unrelated charges brought Secretary of State Rose Mofford to power as governor. Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, a Democrat, has pledged to do whatever is necessary for a King holiday. But while Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> has lobbied quietly for the bill since then, most <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republicans have held fast against it. A recent study estimates the state has lost $ 256 million in convention and tourist business since <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s order, and some Super Bowl boosters say <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>'s bid for the 1993 game is doomed if there's no holiday. But some <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republicans say the holiday is a slap in the face to <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> because it would follow the federal practice of combining holidays for <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> into a single holiday in exchange for a state holiday honoring King. Some <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senators have offered to vote for a bill that would trade in Columbus Day for King Day. But Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> said she rejects that option, and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers say they would prefer to avoid it, even though they consider it a possibility. Religious leaders and business executives have been urging approval of the King holiday for years, but <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers say their constituents do n't agree. Furthermore, they note, many of the businesses that are pushing for the holiday do n't even give their own employees the day off. `` They ought to take a look in the mirror,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, a Republican who is among those targeted by the executives.
