<HEAD>Cheney: No Reason to Question Iowa Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defense Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> says he's satisfied <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials investigating the explosion that killed 47 sailors on the USS Iowa did `` the best job they could. <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> told reporters Monday he had no reason to question the finding that gunners mate <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> apparently caused the blast by inserting a detonating device between bags of gunpowder in the ship's ill-fated No. 2 gun turret `` I do think it's important to point out that the information or the evidence that's available is incomplete,'' <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said in his first extensive public statement about the report. `` We'll never know with absolute certainty exactly what transpired because of the nature of the incident itself,'' he said. In the report issued earlier this month, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said the blast apparently was caused by a detonating device between bags of gunpowder and that the <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON>, the gun captain at the time, was the most likely person to have sabotaged the firing. The report said uncertainty remains, however, because all the witnesses died in the explosion. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials also said they had ruled out technical reason for the blast after conducting some 20,000 tests on the gunpowder and guns used aboard the ship. `` I think the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> did the best job they could under the circumstances on the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. I think the investigation ... was a good one,'' <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said the service did `` a good technical job of checking out all conceivable possibilities by which that incident might have occurred, such as an accident because of the gunpowder exploding prematurely or some other such thing.'' `` I am satisfied with that aspect of it,'' he said. <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON>'s family has criticized the report for singling him out, but <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said Rear Adm. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>, the investigating officer, was required to provide his best conclusion on what happened. `` That's what he's done,'' <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said. `` I do n't have any reason to question it.'' <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday that experiments were being conducted on the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> using an improper number of powder bags combined with the heaviest-weight type of projectile. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> confirmed Monday that experiments took place, but that they did n't cause the explosion. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Cmdr. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON> noted <PERSON> Milligen </PERSON> had included information about the unauthorized tests in his report, and had mentioned the unauthorized use of five bags instead of six bags of powder in the No. 2 gun turret, which exploded. `` The improper loading configuration did not cause, nor did it contribute to, the explosion,'' <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON> said. `` Ditto for the powder.'' The report says such experiments had been conducted aboard the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> from Nov. 4, 1987 until the day of the explosion. The report also notes <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Moosally </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> captain, had approved the use of reduced charge loads, but that he thought that meant six 55-pound bags of powder instead of the larger bags of around 90-110 pounds. <PERSON> Moosally </PERSON> did not have the authority to approve such tests, <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON> said. The report called for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general to look into the unauthorized tests, and Rear Adm. <PERSON> Ming </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> plans to do so, <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON> said. Because of the many improper procedures found aboard the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, such as the gunpowder experiments, it has been left to Adm. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, the chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION>, to decide whether disciplinary action might be taken. The battleship currently is in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>.
