<HEAD>Nation Needs to Raise Level of Learning, Build New Classrooms, Report
Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Educators already strapped by tight budgets as they seek to improve classroom achievements face billions of dollars in maintenance and construction costs in the next few years, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> says. Local school districts, which historically have been responsible for running and paying for their school buildings, have seen maintenance costs increase 64 percent since 1983 _ to $ 41 billion, according to a report the governors' association issued Monday. In addition, existing plans to renovate or build schools are expected to cost $ 84 billion, the association's annual 50-state survey said, warning the costs could undercut direct education programs. `` The projected costs for new school construction and maintenance and repairs for existing schools are so enormous that they can overwhelm policy-makers,'' said the report, called `` Results in Education: 1989.'' `` When these estimates are broken down on a per-student or annual basis over a 20-year period, the price tag may seem more manageable. Still, unless addressed, the problem will mount as aging suburban schools reach the end of their intended life span and urban and rural schools deteriorate further.'' The association said rural schools are particularly pressed, noting another report that described half of the rural schools as being unsafe, outdated and inadequate. In addition, the report said many school districts are seeing money drained from their budgets to finance litigation because of lawsuits. Several states are considering measures to relieve the pressure on local officials by providing state support for school construction costs, said the report. <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON>, the association president, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Garrey </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carruthers </PERSON> released the report a week before the education summit the governors will have with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Charlottesville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` It is time for us as governors to pay careful attention to what is being taught in our schools and to what students are expected to learn,'' <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said. `` Governors are powerful agents of change and the report that we submit today is evidence of that fact.'' <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, said `` the heart of this report is not so much in what the states are doing, but in the introduction and unfinished agenda sections that tell us what we have yet to do to turn our public schools around.'' Key findings of the report included: _ 32 states are improving teacher recruitment and retention Five states now have teacher licensing boards on which a majority of the members are administrators and teachers. Thirteen states are trying to increase the number of minority teachers. _ 41 states report new, expanded or proposed parent involvement policies, including 16 with programs to assist parents in becoming effective teachers at home _ 31 states now offer pre-school and other early childhood programs and 34 states offer alternative programs for high schools _ Nearly half the states use computers to maintain student records, train teachers, evaluate curriculum and instruct students `` Simply stated, restructuring means that we are trying to find better ways to organize our schools, to prepare our teachers and to determine what students must know and be able to do,'' said <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON>.
