<HEAD>Senators Still Seeking Drug Spending Compromise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Meetings scheduled early afternoon EDT, top prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republicans concede President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s anti-drug strategy needs some work, but their talks with Democrats have left the two sides without agreement so far on how it should be reshaped Democratic and <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senators planned to meet again today in their search for a package of anti-drug measures agreeable to lawmakers of both parties. The bargaining, which began Friday, is being fueled by both sides' claim to the lead role in attacking illegal drugs and drug-related crimes, issues party leaders say are uppermost on the public's mind. A two-hour session Monday evening produced no deal. Republicans emerged saying they still supported the $ 7.9 billion package for fiscal 1990, beginning Oct. 1, that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> outlined Sept. 5. And Democrats said they remained behind the $ 10.1 billion plan they countered with a week later, a proposal that garnered a quick veto threat from <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides. `` I do n't think we're at the point yet where we know what they're proposing, other than the president's plan,'' Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, author of the Democratic plan, said after A general profile of a compromise that might ultimately arise did, however, begin to emerge. Sen. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, the Republican's chief negotiator, said <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers `` are willing to help narrow the gap'' between the two sides' spending proposals for treatment and prevention programs. The Democrats want more emphasis on those initiatives than <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sought. <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> also said Republicans supported the Democratic concept of paying for the extra anti-drug spending by cutting other programs across the board. He said the amount the Democrats want to slice off other programs would have to be reduced, and indicated other changes in their plan might be sought as well. `` We agree on more than we disagree upon,'' <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal, which would increase spending over this year's efforts by $ 2.2 billion, would be weighted heavily to law enforcement, prisons and interdiction Prevention and treatment programs would get 27 percent of the total. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> proposed not only beefing up the president's package but changing the distribution. Of the $ 10.1 billion <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> proposes, 65 percent would go to law enforcement and 35 percent to prevention and treatment. That plan, backed by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic leaders, would finance its costs by snipping 0.575 percent from most of the budget. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> identified how he would pay for only about $ 750 million of his proposal, suggesting cuts in a half-dozen other programs. Democrats said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan does not throw enough of a financial punch at the problem. Before <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> introduced his measure, some Democrats said new taxes are needed to adequately finance anti-drug initiatives. But Republicans have complained the Democratic alternative is too costly and provides too much to prevention programs. They also object to the $ 1.8 billion slice the across-the-board cuts would take out of the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 300 billion budget.
