<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Share Prices Also Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar ended lower against the Japanese yen Tuesday, while the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s key index fell marginally. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 1.47 points, or 0.004 percent, closing at 34,471.07. It had gained 70.66 points the previous day. The dollar closed at 145.73 yen, down 0.70 yen from Monday's close of 146.43 yen It opened at 145.70 yen, and moved between 145.59 yen and 146.15 yen. Although the index gained some 100 points soon after the market opened, it turned downward as some market players stopped buying and others sold for profit-taking, said a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` There was no specific element that reversed the upswing. It seemed that participants could not figure out what they should do next after buying aggressively,'' he said. Other dealers said the index started higher as market players were reassured by the yen's rebound against the dollar, but it fell back due to speculative investors' selling to make technical adjustments. In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate was moving nervously around the 146-yen level after opening lower, following a similar downswing on overseas markets overnight, traders said. The dollar then rose as institutional investors bought the dollar near its low. The majority of market players remained on the sidelines, however, ahead of talks among the Group of Seven industrialized nations this weekend, said a trader with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, speaking anonymously. Participating in the <ORGANIZATION> G-7 </ORGANIZATION> meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> will be monetary officials and central bankers from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCA