<HEAD>Generals, Admirals Facing Human Rights Charges To Be Pardoned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> says he will pardon 18 retired generals and admirals who face charges they committed hundreds of human rights abuses in the 1970s during the armed forces' war on leftists. The cases of six other people, including two former presidents already convicted and sentenced, will be considered at a later date, <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> said late Sunday in a brief interview with state-run television. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, who took office in July, said ordered the pardon `` for the good of my country'' and due to the `` need for reconciliation to pacify <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. `` It is not possible to continue living in an ignominious past that wounds us all,'' <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> told Channel 7. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s statement was the first firm indication of who would be included in the controversial pardon, expected to be formally announced after his return Sept. 28 from a visit to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` This is getting worse and worse,'' said <PERSON> Hebe </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonafini </PERSON>, founder of the Mothers of the <ORGANIZATION> Plaza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayo </ORGANIZATION>, a group made up of relatives of people who disappeared during the 1970s. `` All the military is responsible for what happened _ for the kidnappings, the torture and the disappearances.'' Sixteen retired generals and two admirals face trial in civilian courts on hundreds of charges, including kidnapping, torture and murder, growing out of a brutal campaign conducted against leftists during the 1976-83 military regime. Six others were convicted of similar charges in 1984 and are serving terms ranging from eight years to life at a military prison. They are former military presidents <PERSON> Gens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Videla </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Viola </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> commanders Adms. <PERSON> Emilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Massera </PERSON> and <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambruschini </PERSON> and former <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> provincial police chiefs <PERSON> Gens </PERSON>. Ramon Camps and <PERSON> Osvaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Riccheri </PERSON>. A government commission named by <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s predecessor, former President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, determined that at least 8,900 Argentines disappeared during the anti-subversion campaign and were presumed dead. Human rights groups have accused the armed forces of genocide. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, who took office July 8, made no reference to former leftist guerrilla leader <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Firmenich </PERSON>, now serving a 30-year sentence for kidnapping and murder. Unconfirmed reports have indicated his case might be considered along with those of the convicted military men. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> repeatedly has said he intends to resolve the `` military question'' before the end of the year and put an end to civilian-military tension stemming from the trials of officers. But the possibility of a pardon has angered human rights groups, who organized a Sept. 8 opposition march in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> and other major cities. Government officials said Monday the pardon also would include military officers facing disciplinary action for taking part in three insurrections in April 1987 and January and December 1988, during the <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> presidency. The revolts, which were quelled with little bloodshed, were aimed at ending the military trials. The number of those officers facing action never has been announced, but they are estimated to total about 100, including Lt. Col. <PERSON> Aldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rico </PERSON>, leader of the first two revolts, and Col. <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON>, who led the third.
