<HEAD>Last Day of Storm Brings Tornadoes as Grape Growers Assess Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thunderstorms and heavy rains drenched northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> for a third day, dashing hopes of a fruitful grape harvest in the region's wine country. `` We were talking about a very large chardonnay crop this year. We can forget about quantity now and we'll have to see about quality,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckstoffer </PERSON>, the biggest wine grape supplier in <LOCATION> Mendocino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> with 2,000 acres. Growers in <LOCATION> Napa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sonoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mendocino </LOCATION> counties worked in the fields and hoped for sunshine as the sun broke through clouds Monday afternoon after three days of rain. The deluge drenched the vineyards, threatening more than 11,000 acres of grapes that can fetch about $ 1,800 a ton or more. Wine producers were most concerned about the chardonnay and sauvignon blanc fruit, which had been close to maturity before the storm _ the remnants of Hurricane Octave _ struck. The growers hoped hot, dry weather, or at least cool and windy weather, would help negate the effects of the rain. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> forecast fair and warmer weather today and warm, dry weather the rest of the week. `` There's going to be some rot, even if the sun comes out now and everything turns out right,'' said <PERSON> Beckstoffer </PERSON>, whose workers began pulling the leaves out of the bottom of the vines to help them dry faster. `` The thing that scares me is that this -LRB- rain -RRB- might not end. We might be in for the start of cold, wet winter.'' At <ORGANIZATION> Sebastiani </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vineyards </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Sonoma </LOCATION>, vice president and executive winemaster <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said he could see some bunch rot already, especially on the tissue-paper thin skin of chardo