<HEAD>Relief Agencies Need Cash, Few Goods</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government, Puerto Rican communities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and voluntary relief agencies have started relief efforts to help communities struck by Hurricane Hugo. The mobilization came as the storm lashed <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> after battering the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and other tourist havens, leaving at least 14 people dead and tens of thousands homeless. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of the Interior <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, attending a conference in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> with top officials of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territories in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, said Monday $ 500,000 in emergency assistance funds have been released to aid the storm-stricken areas. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said he will leave <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> Wednesday night to return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to plan a tour of the devastation in the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. Gov. <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez-Colon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> said late Monday that <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> left at least 27,900 people homeless. He said he would ask President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to declare the island a disaster area. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, bank accounts, hotlines and phone-a-thons are being set up by the city's <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rican </LOCATION> community to aid hurricane victims. The Department of Puerto Rican Community Affairs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, an organization run by the Commonwealth of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, began to coordinate disaster relief efforts by churches, banks and individuals arou