<HEAD>Beach Boy's Wilson Sues for Rights to Songs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Beach Boy's founder <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> filed a $ 100 million civil suit to recover copyrights to songs that his father sold to A & amp; M Records and an affiliate for $ 700,000 in 1969. The <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> suit Monday charges <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; M with fraud and <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s former attorneys, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Silberberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Knupp </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, with legal malpractice in connection with the sale. It seeks more than $ 50 million in compensatory damages _ the amount <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> alleged A & amp; M earned in publishing royalties from the songs he authored and recorded with the <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION> _ and $ 50 million in punitive damages, said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> was an established writer in 1962 at the age of 19,'' <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> said. `` A performer who has hit songs does not transfer all publishing rights to his future songs to a publishing company for no consideration.'' The suit covers publishing rights to up to 200 songs recorded by the Beach Boys before 1969, <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> said, among them `` Surfin' <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>,'' `` Help Me <PERSON> Rhonda </PERSON>,'' `` Good Vibrations'' and `` California Girls. A spokeswoman at A & amp; M said Monday the firm and its affiliate would have no comment on the suit. Attorneys at <ORGANIZATION> Mitchell </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Silberberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Knupp </PERSON> could not be reached for comment in repeated telephone calls to their offices. The suit contends that <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> was unable to assert his rights to the songs because of his drug and alcohol abuse and psychological illness, the suit claims. The diagnosis of paranoid psychosis that still affects the singer stemmed from childhood abuse by his father, <PERSON> Murry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Murry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> sold the songs because he was upset over his firing as the band's manager in 1964, <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s attorneys, aware of their client's condition, never advised him of his right to assert ownership to the songs, <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> said. In 1962, the year he formed the <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> verbally agreed to allow his father, <PERSON> Murry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, administrative control of his songs, with <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> retaining 100 percent ownership, <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Murry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> set up <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tunes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to administer the songs. In 1969, upset over his firing as the band's manager five years earlier, <PERSON> Murry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> sold his son's publishing rights to the songs to Irving Music for $ 700,000, <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> never saw a penny of it,'' he said. <PERSON> Murry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> died in 1973.
