<HEAD>Sterile Medflies Released in California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two million sterile Medflies have been set loose with a mission to protect <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s fruit crop by messing up the sex lives of their fertile relatives. State officials aboard slowly moving flatbed trucks Monday released the hot-pink irradiated flies from buckets, beginning the state's final assault on a small but worrisome infestation here of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> fruit fly, which destroys fruit crops. `` We want to flood the area with enough sterile flies so that there's almost no possibility that two fertile flies will meet and mate,'' said state entomologist <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Agosta </PERSON>. Twenty-three wild Medflies have been found since Aug. 31. On Sept. 8, helicopters sprayed <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> View </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Sunnyvale </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Altos </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. But Medfly maggots inside fruit and in the ground were not affected by the pesticide. The Medflies are flown in, unhatched, every night from a laboratory in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and are taken to an insect nursery at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> here to hatch By the time the Medfly eradiction program ends early next year, as many as 600 million sterile flies will have been released in a 47-square-mile area.
