<HEAD>Koop Says ``Mean'' Attitude Towards AIDS Victims Must End</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2nd graf to set context of following quote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retiring Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> is urging that the new national AIDS commission try to turn around the `` mean-spiritedness'' some Americans show towards people with AIDS. And the outspoken physician suggests that those who act hatefully toward victims of the incurable disease should be treated in the same way by society. `` You could isolate the mean-spirited people in this country and if the rest of society could treat them with the same repugnance that those people treat persons with AIDS, I think that should be your goal,'' <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> told the commission Monday. <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>, who has sought to heighten awareness about AIDS during his tenure as the nation's top health adviser, also said the government must find a better way to reach teen-agers who are ignoring AIDS warnings. `` We know that sexual activity is rampant and that people of the group I'm talking about are not listening to us,'' he said. <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> spoke to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acquired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deficiency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Syndrome </ORGANIZATION> as it held its first day of testimony from experts, including researchers, advocates and AIDS patients. The panel was created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year to advise the president and <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> on AIDS issues. The latest figures from the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> there are 105,990 Americans diagnosed as having AIDS. Of those, 60 percent are homosexual or bisexual males and 20 percent are intravenous drug users. <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> caused an uproar with his October 1986 report on AIDS in which he advocated sex education for young children. `` I still believe in that very firmly,'' he told the commission. Parents, he said, `` should be joining with and not fighting the schools in getting this done and getting it done properly.'' `` I do believe if we taught sexuality in kind, loving, compassionate, caring ways in a family context that we could raise a generation of teen-agers to be less sexually active than the ones we have today,'' he said. The panel, which met for the first time last month, will take up the work of an earlier AIDS commission formed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and chaired by Adm. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>. That panel called for a major escalation of federal efforts to treat, cure and prevent AIDS and for legislation to protect victims from discrimination. Commission member <PERSON> Belinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, a 30-year-old mother of two who contracted AIDS through a blood transfusion, said the panel can make a difference in the lives of people with AIDS. `` We all want nothing more and nothing less than what all of you take for granted today: a place to live, the right to have a job, decent medical care and to lead their lives without invisible barriers,'' she said. She said she would like to see the commission work for federal protections against discrimination for people with AIDS and for policies that get expensive drug treatments to those who need them. `` Compassion is n't going to happen because of a report we make or an edict that somebody in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> delivers,'' she said. `` It'll begin in the small towns and quiet country throughout <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> where people who live with AIDS and HIV infection are just like us, because they are us.
