<HEAD>Barry Says He Won't Be Drawn Into Controversy about Hand Gesture</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing throughout, with quote from member of
committee to improve city's image.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> says he wo n't be drawn into controversy about an obscene gesture he made to hecklers, but a member of his committee to improve the capital city's image says `` it does n't bode well.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, who says he will run for a fourth term in 1990 despite reported allegations by former associates that he has used drugs, was greeted Sunday with boos and obscene hand gestures from some members of a crowd at an outdoor festival. Smiling, the mayor made an obscene finger gesture. The incident was captured on videotape by a local television station. `` I will not be sidetracked or drawn into responding to insignificant, single incidents that do not affect me or the job the voters of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, elected me to do,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said Monday in a written statement. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, a local public relations executive and member of the mayor's committee to improve the city's image, said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>'s reaction would be normal for many people, but not for a mayor `` I guess we hope that that -LRB- television footage -RRB- does n't make it nationally. It does n't bode well,'' <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> said. One mayoral candidate, <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, called on <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> not to seek re-election, saying the incident shows he is `` essentially politically impotent.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, whose links to a convicted drug dealer are under federal investigation, has repeatedly denied ever using drugs. Officials said about 275,000 people attended the outdoor festival.
