<HEAD>Landlord Convicted in Fire Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A landlord whose rooming house was gutted in a fire that killed eight tenants has been convicted of criminally negligent homicide for code violations that included a door locked with a key from the inside. Two tenants were found dead at the door in the Jan. 15 blaze in <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>. Supreme Court Justice <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Colabella </PERSON> on Monday convicted <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> on two counts of criminally negligent homicide and acquitted the 67-year-old landlord on five others. An eighth count was dismissed earlier. It was believed to be the first time in <LOCATION> Westchester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> that a landlord was held liable for a death because of failure to comply with safety codes. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> could receive one and one-third to four years in prison on each count at sentencing Nov. 2. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rochelle </LOCATION>, had been charged with the eight deaths because of fire code violations that included a missing fire door and a dead bolt on the front door that required a key from the inside to unlock. He was convicted in the deaths of the two men, ages 52 and 61, who were found at the locked door of the four-story building. Investigators said the fire started in the basement and was caused by careless smoking by a drunken resident. The resident died in the blaze. Defense attorney <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Comer </PERSON> said the lack of case law on landlord liability made an appeal `` absolutely necessary.'' <PERSON> Comer </PERSON> had argued that the special lock had been requested by tenants worried about the drug addicts hanging out on the steps. He had also noted that several tenants had been drunk and said that contributed to their inability to get out. District Attorney <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Vergari </PERSON>'s office seized records of city agencies to determine why full inspections had not been done in as much as a decade.
</TEXT>
