<HEAD>Judge Says Federal Feather Permit Process Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The permit process imposed on Pueblo Indians seeking eagle feathers for religious rites is unconstitutional, a federal judge ruled. The process `` constitutes excessive entanglement with the religious tenets of those tribes and is therefore an invalid mixture of church and state,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conway </PERSON> ruled Friday. Eagle feathers are available to Pueblos only by applying to a depository maintained by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Conway </PERSON>'s ruling came in the case of <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Suazo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinds </PERSON>, a Pueblo charged in the purchase of a golden eagle for $ 500 that he resold to a cousin. The case stems from a Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> sting that netted hundreds of arrests in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> in January. `` The most significant thing to me in the opinion is that this court has recognized that Indian religious practices are entitled to just as much protection as anybody else's religion,'' said defense attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON> said he is unsure whether he will appeal. But he said, `` There's no question that the transfer of the eagle was for money, and we do n't think Indian religious freedom was an issue.'' <PERSON> Hinds </PERSON> says he sold the eagle at no profit to his cousin, who needed it after he was to be initiated into a pueblo religious society. The cousin tried for two years to get an eagle through the federal depository, the defense argued. The prosecution contended that <PERSON> Hinds </PERSON> bought the eagle to make a fetish for a non-Indian psychiatrist for several thousand dollars. But the judge ruled that the prosecution failed to establish any motive other than religious convictions. The judge also noted that Pueblos whose applications are granted get frozen eagles that often are killed by non-Indians in an unspecified manner. Some Indian rituals forbid use of a dead eagle; others designate how the eagle should be killed, he said. <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>, a Pueblo anthropologist, testified at a hearing that <PERSON> Pueblo </PERSON> religion would `` wither away'' without eagle feathers but that the plumes are available only through a cumbersome and intrusive process. `` The federal depository has a special problem because one may apply, but one never knows when or even if you'll get the feathers you need,'' he said. `` It's very sad that <PERSON> Pueblo </PERSON> peoples who still practice their traditional religion have to rely on such a system.''
</TEXT>
