chev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he first wanted to await results of the <LOCATION> Baker-Shevardnadze </LOCATION> meeting. A superpower summit is expected to be one issue on the agenda. Suggesting that Soviet intentions still leave a lot to be desired, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` We have interests in this hemisphere where the Soviets are continuing to send ... increased amounts of arms going into <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> right now over last year. That's not very good. That's not a very kind and gentle approach to this hemisphere.'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said Monday that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has reacted timidly to events in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and should actively support the forces of democratic change in the communist world. He called on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to support the entry of communist nations into Western economic institutions, `` once their internal reforms merit such participation.'' `` Now is the time for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to encourage and capitalize upon the changes we have sought for so long,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said in a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> speech. `` The administration's timidity in the face of these opportunities is puzzling and dismaying. Instead of encouragement and engagment, the administration has adopted an almost passive stance.'' On another issue involving <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he did not fear for his safety or for that of his family because of reported death threats from Colombian drug lords, saying he had confidence in the Secret Service. He said there was `` no hard intelligence evidence'' of the targeting of his family or of any other Americans by drug interests in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. `` But, clearly, any such act