<HEAD>Vatican Supports Moving Nuns from Auschwitz Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th pvs, `The agreement...' to UPDATE
with Glemp comment in Britain. Pick up 7th pvs, `The archbishop...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> said today that a Roman Catholic convent of Carmelite nuns near the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> death camp in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> should be moved to another site, as Jewish groups have sought. Breaking its silence on an issue that has severely strained Jewish-Catholic relations, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> said it would help to pay for a prayer center in which the nuns would live. Jewish leaders in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> applauded the statement and said it would improve Jewish-Catholic relations. A February 1987 accord between Jewish and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> representatives stipulated that the nuns would be moved to the prayer center from a convent just outside <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. Jews have objected to their presence at a site where 2.5 million Jews were murdered by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> during World War II. However, the Polish primate, Cardinal <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>, has called for renegotiating the agreement and said the Polish church did not have the money to build a new home for the nuns. The agreement, signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, called for the nuns to have been moved by Feb. 22, but the deadline passed and the nuns remained. <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>, on a 24-hour visit to <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, to consecrate a Polish Catholic church, indicated he had not read the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> statement. Based on what reporters had told him about the statement, he said: `` this would seem to be a forceful resolution of the problem and I do n't think that would be a very positive way of resolving it.'' But <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> also said `` there is a possibility that the nuns could move elsewhere.'' `` But if they were to be moved, this should be done with charity because even if we were to transfer these nuns to a different location, that would also be crossing out their rights,'' he said. The archbishop of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>, Cardinal <PERSON> Franciszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Macharski </PERSON>, said last month that the church was abrogating the agreement since it could not be fulfilled in an atmosphere of aggressive demands. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s Commission for Religious Relations with <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION> said in a communique today that it was pleased with a declaration from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s bishops earlier this month that Roman Catholics and Jewish groups should resume talks on building a prayer center in which the nuns would live. `` The Holy See is convinced that such a center would contribute in an important way to development of good relations between Christians and Jews,'' the communique said. The Rev. Pier <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Fumagalli </PERSON>, secretary of the commission, told reporters he expected the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> declaration would be honored. But he added `` I ca n't forsee what will happen in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.'' He said the questions of exactly where, when and how the prayer center would be built were being left to Polish church officials. Asked whether the pope had approved the communique, a <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> spokesman, the Rev. <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Ercole </PERSON>, noted the statement had been published in the official <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> bulletin _ implying papal acceptance. <PERSON> Elan </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said that because of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> communique, his organization had decided to recommend to its constituencies around the world that they suspend their freeze on contacts with the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. `` We welcome this very important step in restoring the good word of the church. It's time to move on and implement the agreement,'' he said. Rabbi <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hier </PERSON>, dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weisenthal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said the communique was a major policy reversal by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> that would remove a stumbling block in Catholic-Jewish relations. `` The issue was never over the rights of non-Jews to pray at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hier </PERSON> said. `` The issue was the building of permanent structures at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>.'' An estimated 2.5 million of the 4 million victims of <LOCATION> Auschwitz-Birkenau </LOCATION> were Jewish, and the convent's opponents argue that it is deeply offensive that Christian religious symbols tower over what is in effect their gravesite. <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> has called the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accord `` offensive,'' and he provoked further controversy with remarks deemed by many to be anti-Semitic. An estimated 1.5 million Christians also were killed at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. The proposal to remove the convent founded in 1984 just outside the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> fence has found little sympathy among Poles. They argue that the nuns are not harming anyone and that thousands of the victims at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> were Polish political prisoners, including many priests and nuns. The issue has also caused divisions among cardinals. Last weekend, Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said he supported Jewish efforts to move the nuns and that he was exploring talking to <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> about the dispute. Jewish groups have asked the Polish-born pope to step in and settle the controversy. But until today's announcement, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> had left it up to the Polish church to settle.
