<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An under-cuddled German teddy bear fetched a world record $ 86,000 at an auction Tuesday, more than four times the previous highest price for a teddy bear and 60 times its catalogue estimate, <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s said. `` When I told the owner the news, he said: ` I think that works out at 1,000 pounds -LRB- $ 1,570 -RRB- a hair.' He was very pleased and very happy,'' said <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s appraiser <PERSON> Bunny </PERSON> <PERSON> Campione </PERSON>. The two-tone bear, made by German manufacturer <ORGANIZATION> Steiff </ORGANIZATION> in 1920, has unusually large eyes that `` make it look a little forlorn'' and is in such good condition `` it does n't look as if it has been cuddled very much,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Campione </PERSON> said the bear had been expected to sell for up to $ 7,800 but had earlier been listed in an auction house catalogue at $ 1,100 to $ 1,400. `` There is no justifiable reason why it made so much money,'' she said in a telephone interview. The previous highest auction price for a teddy bear was $ 19,000, paid at a Christie's auction in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on May 18 for a Steiff bear made between 1906 and 1909 for Princess <LOCATION> Xenia </LOCATION>, a cousin of Czar <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s record-busting bear is 24 inches long, has plush fur in blond and brown, amber-and-black glass eyes measuring about 1 inch in diameter, swivel joints, a humped back and widely spaced ears. The buyer, represented by a British agent, insisted on anonymity. The bear had belonged to an unidentified British man who inherited it from his grandmother, Mrs. <PERSON> Campione </PERSON> said. `` The grandmother considered him -LRB- the bear -RRB- to be very much her own and kept him away from the children who were allowed to see him but not to play with him,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Campione </PERSON>, a fine-doll expert, said she was baffled by the sale price for a bear that was hardly rare. `` A few thousand were made in 1920 instead of a few million,'' but it is in unusually `` superb condition,'' she said. `` Most of them are cuddled or kissed on the nose so much that the nose gets dented in, or get dragged around the garden by children.'' She speculated that the buyer may want the bear as a prototype for limited edition. At the first teddy bear auction organized by Mrs. <PERSON> Campione </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s in 1982, the most expensive teddy went for $ 630. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Steiff </PERSON>'s lovable creations took the world by storm at the <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION> toy fair in 1903, and valuable teddies are now almost exclusively made by <PERSON> Steiff </PERSON> at the village of <LOCATION> Giengen </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.
