<HEAD>Vermont Justice Found Guilty of Misconduct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today that one of its retired justices was guilty of judicial misconduct for helping a female friend who was a lower-court judge. The ruling said retired Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> committed seven ethics violations, primarily for sitting on cases involving former Assistant Judge <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheel </PERSON> and for intimidating the state attorney general by personally delivering a letter urging that a criminal probe of Wheel be speeded up. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, 72, was one of three <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justices charged with misconduct in 1987 by the <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conduct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of the court. The board alleged the three improperly used their clout to help Wheel, then an assistant judge in <LOCATION> Chittenden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, in a variety of matters. The charges threw the five-member court into turmoil. Gov. <PERSON> Madeleine </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunin </PERSON> asked the three to step aside while the accusations were examined. They refused, but disqualified themselves from all cases involving anyone involved in the complaints, which affected hundreds of cases. The charges against Justice <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> were dropped for lack of a case. Justice <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> died before the allegations against him were resolved. A court employee testified that Wheel had been seen with her arms around <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wheel </PERSON> testified they were not close and did not have an affair. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> described their relationship as collegial. The <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conduct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> found <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> guilty of 11 counts of misconduct, but it was up to the state's high court to decide <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s fate Today, the high court dismissed four counts but upheld the others. `` A judge can never avoid the prestige and authority of the office he or she holds,'' said the court. `` That prestige and authority, however, may not be used to enhance personal relationships, or for selfish reasons, or to bestow favors.'' The court said it would hear arguments next week on what sanctions to impose against <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>. Because <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> is retired, the sanctions range from a reprimand to suspension from service as a substitute justice on high court cases. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s pension will not be affected. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Marks </PERSON>, said he and <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> felt the decision was a `` mixed bag.'' The case was heard by a specially assigned court since most of the members who sat on the court with <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> disqualified themselves. Wheel was convicted in a separate criminal case involving allegations she billed the state for days she did not work.
