<HEAD>Plane Forced to Land by Gunman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with all passengers, crew freed,
CORRECTS make of aircraft; picks up 4th pvs: An official.. .</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS PALMAS, Canary Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gunman forced a Moroccan passenger plane flying across the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> to land today on Grand Canary island, officials said. The police officer at <LOCATION> Gando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> said the two crew members and six passengers were allowed to leave the ATR-42 twin-engine turboprop about two hours after it touched down on this Spanish archipelago at 2:45 p.m. The unidentified gunman gave himself up about six hours after the aircraft landed, said the officer, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said no concessions were made to the gunman but had no information on a possible motive for the hijacking. The <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maroc </ORGANIZATION> aircraft was initially identified as a <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> by police. An official in the <LOCATION> Gando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> control tower, who would not give his name, said by telephone that the gunman had demanded to talk with the local representative of the Moroccan national airline in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palmas </LOCATION>. An attendant at the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maroc </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palmas </LOCATION> said the flight had left the eastern town of <LOCATION> Smara </LOCATION> in the Moroccan-occupied <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> on a scheduled domestic flight west to the city of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aaiun </LOCATION>. Grand <LOCATION> Canary </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> is 135 miles west of the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. The incident occurred prior to the first official visit to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> on Sunday by Moroccan King <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> II. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> abandoned the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> in 1975, and <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> sent thousands of civilians to occupy the area. The <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> is also claimed by the <ORGANIZATION> Polisario </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, which has been waging a desert guerrilla war against the Moroccan army since 1975.
