<HEAD>Authorities Arrest Suspect in 1.25-Ton Silver Heist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> man has been charged with stealing 1.25 tons of silver shaped like <ORGANIZATION> Hershey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kisses </ORGANIZATION> from a <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> mine where he once worked, authorities said today. Sheriff <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON> said officials hoped to get arrest warrants today or Wednesday for two other <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> people wanted in the Trinity Mine heist Aug. 26. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Aiden </PERSON>, 22, of Billings, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, was arrested Saturday and jailed on $ 105,000 bail on charges of embezzlement and conspiracy, <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON> said. The $ 200,000-plus cache of partially processed silver is still missing. The heist occurred when two shotgun-toting masked robbers bound two mine employees with duct tape and then took more than an hour in the middle of the night to haul the 1.25 tons of silver into a waiting pickup. The robbers then left spikes in the road to flatten tires of pursuers. Police immediately theorized the heist was commited by people with inside information. Authorities were led to <PERSON> Aiden </PERSON> based on interviews with past and present mine workers that revealed several small silver thefts at the mine, <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON> said. `` Once information about some other minor silver thefts began surfacing, people started getting nervous and talking,'' <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON> said. Officials gave lie detector tests to past and present employees of the mine, 90 miles northeast of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>.
