<HEAD>EDs: Top 8 grafs new with Baker comments on Soviet aid to Nicaragua.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, The State Department.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said today continued <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> weapons shipments to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> will be a priority issue when he meets later this week with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. `` We're a little disappointed in what's going on down there,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said, referring to the role of the Soviets and other <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc countries in building up the Sandinista military arsenal. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told a news conference that most of the Soviet weaponry arrives in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> via third countries. He added that the Soviets could put a stop to the practice if they so chose. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Monday in <LOCATION> Helena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, that the increased flow of Soviet bloc arms to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> indicates `` not a very kind and gentle approach to this hemisphere.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke after the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Soviet bloc weapons deliveries to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> have continued at a rate of more than one a week this year, despite a cease-fire dating back 18 months. Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> pledged early this year to cut off weapons deliveries to the <LOCATION> Sandinistas </LOCATION>. But administration officials, insisting on anonymity, said <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> weapons were spotted last week being loaded onto a Nicaraguan vessel at a port in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. The equipment has since been delivered to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The officials declined comment on a published report that the weapons consisted of three torpedo-carrying boats and four Mi-24 Hind helicopters. The leak of that sensitive information seemed calculated to influence the upcoming meeting Friday and Saturday between <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. One purpose of the meeting is to lay the groundwork for a summit meeting between <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that Soviet bloc deliveries to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for the first eight months of this year totaled about $ 350 million. The equipment weighed an estimated 12,000 tons and was delivered during 41 ship visits to Nicaraguan ports, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said, adding that the value of such shipments during all of 1988 was $ 515 million. Earlier Monday, spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> expressed irritation that overall deliveries to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> appear to have increased this year compared with a similar period in 1988. Officials had expected a decline since the Sandinista government and the Nicaraguan resistance reached agreement on a truce in March 1988. Although there have been some violations of the truce, the level of fighting is down sharply from 1987. Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said the level of Soviet bloc shipments is well beyond the legitimate defense needs of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. `` It is inexplainable to us why the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bloc </LOCATION> feels that it must provide <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> with even more weapons while a cease-fire is in effect than it provided the Nicaraguans when they were actively engaged with Contra forces,'' she said. `` The basic pattern in recent years has been transshipment of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> weapons through <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. `` This year, the weapons out of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has increased dramatically.'' Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> also said <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> continue to supply arms to the leftist <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> has come to rely chiefly on Soviet bloc weapons,'' she said, adding that such activity defies agreements signed by Central American presidents which call for an end to outside support for insurgencies in the region.
