<HEAD>Kremlin Official Says Those Leaving USSR Aren't Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teton-Tete-a-Tete, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Kremlin's top human rights official took issue Tuesday with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> definition of Soviet emigres as refugees, saying it creates `` friction'' in superpower relations at a time when his government is allowing record numbers of citizens to leave. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanitarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> and Cultural Relations at the Soviet foreign ministry, was in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for talks with the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> preparatory to the meeting later this week between Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> said the agenda, at the request of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side, would include discussion of the cases of several hundred Soviet Jews denied permission to emigrate. The two sides will also discuss exchange programs for psychiatrists and law enforcement officers, he said. In an unusual appearance before the National Conference on Soviet Jewry, <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> promised that Soviet Jews would be allowed to practice their religion freely or leave the country if they want. New draft laws on freedom of religion and on emigration seek to `` create the best possibilities for those who want to live in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. ... But for those who, for some reason, are unhappy and want to leave, the best civilized conditions should be created,'' he said. In the first eight months of the year, 127,000 Soviets were allowed to emigrate, he said, about a third of whom came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as refugees whose expenses were paid by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government. Speaking to reporters after his speech, <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> criticized the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy of classifying the Soviet emigres as refugees, saying it runs `` contrary to the definition of refugee'' accepted by the international community. `` Calling these people refugees creates a considerable, additional friction'' in U.S.-Soviet relations. `` We are trying to do our best to solve the situation but then ... we're -LRB- portrayed as -RRB- some enemy of mankind from whom all the people are fleeing. It's not a good thing,'' <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> said. Deputy Secretary of State <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>, addressing the conference before <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON>, defended the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan to allot 50,000 of the 125,000 worldwide refugee slots in fiscal year 1990 to Soviet emigres. Despite the unprecedented surge of Soviets allowed to emigrate, and the recent improvement in the lives of those staying behind, there are still hundreds denied permission to leave and a wave of anti-Semitism has surfaced as a result of the glasnost policies of free expression, <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> said. `` Given the history'' of hundreds of years of officially sanctioned anti-Semitism, `` tens of thousands of Soviet Jews are turning to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> said. `` What Soviet Jews are looking for now is a plcae where they can be themselves. They are not economic migrants.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is `` a victim of our success'' now that the Soviets have acceded to years of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demands to allow free emigration, he said. Unfortunately, budget constraints place a limit on the number of Soviets the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can absorb and other countries, such as <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, should share the burden, he added. <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> promised that <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> would bring up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concerns about anti-Semitism in his meeting with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and would press for enactment of legislation that will institutionalize the reforms. Once such laws are adopted, he said, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will lift certain trade restrictions on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> is `` lobbying'' the Supreme Soviet, which is the Soviet legislature, to consider the draft laws as soon as possible and at least one may be taken up at the coming session starting Sept. 25. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had anticipated the new laws would have been enacted already, but <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> said the Supreme Soviet has other items higher on its agenda. The Soviet official said that even without the laws, the number of people denied emigration dropped from 11,000 several years ago to 2,000, the teaching of Hebrew and Yiddish is allowed in schools, and three million Bibles were recently imported into the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> promised that all violators of the ban on anti-Semitic activity would be punished. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says that despite the official outlawing of discrimination against Jews, anti-Semitism among the lower echelons of the bureacracy and among the general population has increased.
