<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> PORT-AU-PRINCE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The president has commuted the life sentence of <PERSON> Luc </PERSON> <PERSON> Desir </PERSON>, the former secret police chief who directed hundreds of torture sessions during the <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> regime, a state-run newspaper said Tuesday. Human rights activist <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Bajeux </PERSON> immediately denounced the move, saying: `` The commutation is a gesture of conciliation toward the Duvalierists. The next step is a full pardon.'' `` <PERSON> Luc </PERSON> <PERSON> Desir </PERSON>, the man who directed torture sessions with a Bible in his hand, is a symbol of Duvalierist barbarity,'' <PERSON> Bajeux </PERSON> said in an interview. L'Union newspaper carried an <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement saying that on the first anniversary of his rise to power on Sept. 17, 1988, the president, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Prosper </PERSON> <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>, pardoned or commuted the sentences of 13 people. They included <PERSON> Desir </PERSON>, who was sentenced to life at hard labor after the fall of dictator <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> in 1986. <PERSON> Desir </PERSON>'s sentence was commuted to 30 years in prison, the <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement said `` The president of the republic has the prerogative to commute a sentence. If he so wishes, he may even grant full pardon,'' <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Kernizan </PERSON>, the secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Port-au-Prince </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kernizan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Desir </PERSON>'s trial had been irregular and that he was `` a victim of social pressure.'' <PERSON> Kernizan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Desir </PERSON>'s `` victims could not testify against him, since most of them are dead.'' One of the few people to be sentenced for crimes committed under the dictatorship, <PERSON> Desir </PERSON> directed innumerable torture sessions and executions when he headed the dreaded secret police of <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON>'s father. The number of his victims is not known, but they are estimated in the hundreds. In the 1970s <PERSON> Desir </PERSON> fell out of favor with <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> and was forced into retirement. He was captured while trying to flee the country on Feb. 25, 1988. An airport employee alerted a local radio station of his flight, and thousands of Haitians swarmed the landing strip to prevent his departure. <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> `` Papa Doc'' <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> was elected president in 1957 following a year of political turmoil during which six different governments held power. He became president-for-life in 1964 and wielded absolute political control until his death in 1971, when his son, <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> `` Baby Doc'' <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>, assumed the presidency. On Feb. 7, 1986, after months of civil disorder, <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> fled to exile in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> led the military junta that assumed power when <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> fled. Presidential elections on Nov. 29, 1987, were aborted after thugs, protected by soldiers, massacred at least 34 voters at polling stations. Civilian <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> won army-run elections on Jan. 17, 1988, and was overthrown by <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> on June 20, 1988. On Sept. 17, 1988, a military coup brought <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> to power. In April 1989, loyalist troops foiled a coup attempt and crushed a rebellion by two army units. <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> comprises the western third of the island of Hispaniola in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, between <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>.
