<HEAD>Baker Aims for Progress on Arms Pacts, Raps Mitchell</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files, edits and adds information throughout; corrects
quote in pvs 5th graf, Baker replied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said today he hoped to conclude a chemical weapons agreement with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> this weekend and make headway on other arms control fronts. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, in his first <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> news conference in eight months in his job, sought to reverse growing criticism in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and elsewhere of the cautious approach President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is taking in response to foreign policy initiatives from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. He accused the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s Democratic leader of playing politics with the issue. Last week, Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, who will meet with <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, on Friday and Saturday, accused the administration of `` timidity'' on arms control issues. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, said Monday that the administration had failed to encourage change in the Eastern bloc and was `` feeling almost nostalgic about the Cold War.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> replied today: `` The president is rocking along with a 70 percent approval rating in foreign policy. And if I were the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader I might have something like that to say, too.'' And yet, in several of his replies to questions, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> stressed the cautious stance taken by the administration toward Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> would be maintained. `` I hope we have been approaching this relationship with a proper degree of prudence,'' he said. In this regard, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> lowered expectations that he would set a date with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> for a summit meeting between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. He said only that the subject would be thoroughly discussed at Jackson Hole. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said any increases in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, which are veering away from a Marxist economy, depended on the changes undertaken in the two East European countries. `` We should n't be mistaken'' and think <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid could overcome their problems, he said. And, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said, it was the Soviets' `` turn to move'' on reducing troops and non-nuclear armaments in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. On negotiating arms control with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said, `` we have to be careful not to become frantic ...'' However, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said he would propose to <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> ways to break a 15-year impasse on verifying the size of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet underground nuclear tests. In addition, he said, `` We have, I think, a reasonable shot at an agreement to exchange data on chemical stocks, which I think is a first practical step toward achieving real controls and eventually a total ban.'' On another arms control front, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the administration no longer would seek a ban on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet long-range mobile missiles. He urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to provide funds for development of the single-warhead Midgetman. The move is of limited significance. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had taken the position it favored a ban only if the elimination of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet mobile missiles could be verified, and no headway was made on the issue in negotiations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said continued <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> weapons shipments to leftist <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> will be a priority issue in his discussions with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. `` We're a little disappointed in what's going on down there,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said, referring to the role of the Soviets and other <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc countries in building up the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>' military arsenal. He said most of the Soviet weaponry arrives in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> via third countries and the Soviets could put a stop to the practice if they so chose.
