<HEAD>Appeals Court Awards America's Cup to San Diego</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: COMBINES pvs urgent series, ADDS background, editing throughout.
No pickup. ADDS byline. A version moving on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state appeals court today stripped <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> of the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Cup and gave the trophy back to the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yacht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s Appellate Division reversed a lower court ruling April 7 that stripped <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> of yacht racing's most coveted prize for using a catamaran, or two-hull vessel, instead of a single-hull boat in winning a 1988 match. The appeals court said that the catamaran was legal and that the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> is entitled to the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Cup. <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciparick </PERSON> had ruled in April that the best-of-three race between the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, a yacht about 90 feet at the water line sailed by the <ORGANIZATION> Mercury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, and the Stars and Stripes, a 60-foot catamaran sailed by the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> group, was a `` gross mismatch'' and unfair. <PERSON> Ciparick </PERSON> found that competing vessels must be `` somewhat evenly matched'' in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Cup competition and that using a lighter, faster catamaran violated the spirit of the international competition. But in its 4-1 decision today the appeals court said <PERSON> Ciparick </PERSON> had on her own pronounced a rule that is neither expressed nor implied in the Deed of Gift, the 102-year-old document that governs the race. The squabbling began in July 1987 when <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Fay </PERSON>, on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> Mercury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, ignored modern <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Cup tradition and demanded a one-on-one match with a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> defender. <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> wanted the race held within one year rather than the usual three to four; he wanted a one-on-one race instead of the usual elimination matches, and he wanted to compete in a boat more than 90 feet long at the water line instead of the usual yachts that are about 45 feet at the water line. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> rejected the challenge, but <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> went to court. When <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> was ordered to accept the challenge, it also went to an unconventional boat, the speedy catamaran. The <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yacht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> became trustee of the Cup in 1987 after skipper <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> sailed the 12-meter yacht <ORGANIZATION> Stars </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Stripes to victory over the Australian defender, <PERSON> Kookaburra </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, in waters off <LOCATION> Fremantle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. The victory returned the Cup to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Conner </PERSON>'s 1983 loss to the Australians ended a 132-year <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> winning streak.
