<HEAD>Events in the Convent Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Auschwitz-Vatican, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are dates of significant events in the controversy surrounding the convent of Carmelite nuns near the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> death camp site: June 1984 _ Ten Polish nuns receive permission from the Polish government to turn a former <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> storehouse on the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> death camp perimeter into a convent. They move in shortly thereafter. Feb. 22, 1987 _ Eighteen Jewish and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> leaders sign agreement in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to move the convent by 1989 to an interfaith prayer and education center to be located further from the site. Feb. 22, 1989 _ Deadline passes and nuns remain in the convent. July 14, 1989 _ An <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> rabbi and six other Jews stage a five-hour protest and are forcibly removed by workers after trying to scale a convent wall. Aug. 10, 1989 _ Cardinal <PERSON> Franciszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Macharski </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>, whose diocese includes the convent, says the 1987 agreement to move the nuns is being abrogated because of the `` aggressive'' atmosphere surrounding the controversy. Aug. 26, 1989 _ Polish primate Cardinal <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> calls a Jewish request to relocate the convent `` offensive'' to Poles and makes other remarks that provoke charges of anti-Semitism by critics. Sept. 19, 1989 _ The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> says the convent should be moved to another site and that it would help finance the construction of an interfaith prayer center for the nuns to live in.
