<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionPlan     09-19 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Plan,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pa. Lawmaker Unveils Pro-Choice Abortion Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A coalition of pro-choice lawmakers Tuesday proposed legislation designed to strengthen women's rights to abortion in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and to preempt a planned attempt to toughen existing laws restricting abortion. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> is widely viewed as a key battleground state following the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision in July that gave states more leeway in addressing the abortion issue. Historically, the state <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> has overwhelmingly approved bills restricting abortions, but many of the provisions have been struck down in court. The new nine-bill package includes measures calling for a state constitutional amendment giving women the right to an abortion, restoring state-subsidized funding for all `` medically necessary'' abortions, and wiping out an existing law requiring rape and incest victims to file a police report before receiving subsidized abortions. The centerpiece bill, sponsored by state Rep. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON>, says government should not interfere with `` a woman's personal choice to commence, prevent or continue a pregnancy or have an abortion'' before the fetus is viable. The proposal mirrors existing law in saying an abortion on a viable fetus is allowed only if the mother's life or health is threatened by the pregnancy. Under the proposal, a fetus is considered viable if the woman's doctor rules there is `` a reasonable likelihood of sustained survival ... outside the woman's uterus. In an attempt to placate some abortion opponents, Ms. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> said the bill would also require doctors to ask teen-age patients to notify at least one parent before having an abortion. If that is not feasible, the doctor must recommend that the teen-ager discuss the matter with another relative, school counselor or another adult. `` This bill represents mainstream <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and the opinion of an overwhelming majority of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> citizens as well, that government has no business invading the privacy of people's lives,'' Ms. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> said at a news conference. The bills are scheduled to be introduced simultaneously in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Oct. 2. Abortion foes, led by state Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Freind </PERSON>, are scheduled to introduce legislation outlining further restrictions on Oct. 3. This is the first attempt in several years to offer an organized pro-choice package of bills. Ms. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> and others acknowledged the proposals would face tough opposition in both chambers, but she said the public generally supports a woman's right to an abortion, even though many legislators do not. Freind said the parental notification in Ms. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON>'s bill weakens what already is in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> law but is under court challenge. The law now requires that a parent be notified or the minor obtain a court order before having an abortion. He also said pro-choice advocates want to restore the pre-1985 situation of `` tax-funded birth control by abortion on demand. That wo n't happen.'' Legislation enacted in the early 1980s and upheld by the courts after years of legal battles restricted Medicaid funding for abortions except in cases of rape or incest or when the mother's life was at stake Abortion already is an issue in the 1990 governor's race. Likely <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Hafer </PERSON> is pro-choice. Incumbent Democrat <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> opposes abortion. Freind has said his bills will deal with such issues as requiring spousal notification before an abortion is performed and banning so-called sex-selection abortions. He said he did n't regard the pro-choice announcement as an attempt to upstage his efforts. `` Nobody takes us out of our game plan,'' he said. `` This is one more battle that has to be won ... It's one more battle that will be won and take us one step closer to the day when the sanctity of all human life is protected in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
