<FIRST>u a AM-AIDS-Drugs Bjt   09-19 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Drugs, Bjt,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: AIDS Patients Take Risks by Combining Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 AIDS patients in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> are taking an average of five drugs and unapproved treatments without telling their doctors, posing a risk of potentially fatal drug interactions, a survey has found. One patient admitted using 25 treatments, said Dr. <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenblatt </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. She described her findings Tuesday at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microbiology </ORGANIZATION>. `` There is a significant minority who have a background belief that new experimental drugs may have more benefit than drugs already available,'' she said. The hidden use of AIDS drugs also makes it difficult for scientists to determine which drugs have toxic side effects. Patients receiving only the recommended, approved treatments for infection with the AIDS virus or HIV would normally not be receiving more than one or two drugs unless they were very sick. Then they might be given up to five drugs, <PERSON> Greenblatt </PERSON> said. Dr. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunnigan </PERSON>, medical director of a city-supported AIDS clinic in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said he was a bit surprised at how many drugs patients were taking, but said he was `` fully supportive of people with HIV using alternative therapies.'' `` I also believe care is difficult if we only have bits and pieces of information'' about what patients are taking, <PERSON> Dunnigan </PERSON> said. He is on the board of the <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> group studying alternative treatments. <PERSON> Greenblatt </PERSON>'s survey found that 37 percent of the patients were getting prescriptions from a second doctor and 28 percent were using treatments not approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` The use of FDA-unapproved treatments was common and increased with the severity of illness,'' <PERSON> Greenblatt </PERSON> said. The only government-approved drug to treat AIDS is AZT. Several other drugs are available for the treatment of AIDS-related infections. The alternative treatments most widely used by patients in the survey included megadoses of vitamin C and the unapproved AIDS drugs AL721 and dextran sulfate. One patient was getting injections of fetal sheep blood. Other doctors familiar with the survey were surprised at how many drugs patients were getting from other doctors and alternative sources, such as community-organized trials of unapproved drugs. AIDS patients have more toxic drug reactions than do other patients, <PERSON> Greenblatt </PERSON> said. Because of the clandestine use of multiple drugs, `` it can be hard to sort out which medications are causing these toxicities,'' she said. The hidden use of approved and unapproved AIDS drugs is complicating scientific research, because subjects in the studies are not disclosing their use of other drugs, <PERSON> Dunnigan </PERSON> said. In some cases, disclosing that use might result in their being dropped from the study, losing access to medical care associated with the study, he said. `` There are two sides,'' he said. `` From the physician's point of view, in order to get good data there needs to be some rigor in how the drugs are used. But from a client's point of view, there's so little that can be done. And the clock keeps ticking.'' <PERSON> Greenblatt </PERSON> said patients who use unapproved treatments are not discharged from her clinic, but are advised to tell their doctors what drugs they are taking. `` I do n't think you can ask people to not take something they think will help them,'' <PERSON> Greenblatt </PERSON> said. `` That's my personal opinion. But you can ask them to let you know.'' The key to avoiding problems is a partnership between doctors and their patients, <PERSON> Dunnigan </PERSON> said, in which patients feel free to disclose which drugs they're taking. `` Hopefully that agreement would be made before therapy is initiated,'' he said. The survey, which began last fall and will continue for two more years, consists of 30-minute to 60-minute interviews with each patient every three months. Patients are asked about their use of various medical services in addition to drug use, <PERSON> Greenblatt </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
