<TEXT>
 A woman's dying wish to leave behind an unimpeded view of the shore by having her house leveled was denied Tuesday by a judge who called the will request a waste of money. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Needham </PERSON> threw out a portion of <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s will that instructed the city of <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> to raze the old home and use the property as a right of way to <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. `` To destroy the house would be to commit substantial waste of this estate,'' <PERSON> Needham </PERSON> said. `` I declare the provision is void as being contrary to public policy.'' <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Trust </LOCATION>, executor of the woman's estate, did not want the nine-room home razed and challenged the will in June, when <ORGANIZATION> Needham </ORGANIZATION> heard arguments from lawyers. In 1973, the <LOCATION> Victorian-Queen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Anne </LOCATION> home built in the 1890s was made a national historic site, along with the rest of the neighborhood. Neighbors and the city also opposed leveling the house and filling in the basement as requested in the will. Ms. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> died in April 1986 at age 86. The will left $ 5,000 to the city to maintain the right of way. The <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> leads to <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Needham </PERSON> said the area would not be served by tearing down the house, among $ 1.4 million in assets left by the woman. Her wealth was mostly in stocks and bonds. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Riedel </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>'s lawyer, said the ruling `` made a lot of sense.'' He added: `` No one wants to see a nice house destroyed. But on the other hand, some people -LRB- would feel -RRB- you ought to be able to do whatever you want in the will.'' <LOCATION> Needham </LOCATION> ruled the home should be sold. He said an appeal of his decision is unlikely. The exact value of the house is unknown, but real estate agents said waterfront homes in the area were selling for $ 400,000 and more.
