<TEXT>
 Two drug addicts from the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> have been admitted to a donated treatment program in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> that could be a model for programs elsewhere in the nation, government and private drug abuse officials announced Tuesday. `` This effort has brought a cooperative spirit to the district that could well be recreated in communities across the nation,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleber </PERSON>, deputy director for demand reduction in the Office of National Drug Control Policy. `` We need everybody to follow this example of private and public cooperation to win this war.'' The two unidentified adult men, who left <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last Wednesday to be admitted to a facility of the <ORGANIZATION> Bradford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, are the first of 70 that the private drug and alcohol treatment organization has said it will accept in the first year of its new program. <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>, a company operated for profit, has had a policy of making unused beds available to uninsured addicts in the <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> area and announced on May 23 that it would extend the program to the nation's capital. Patients for the treatment slots are selected by a committee of private citizens working under auspices of the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Alcoholism and Drug Abuse. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, executive director of the council, said the patients must be residents of the district, must have a `` significant person'' to help them with decisions, must have no criminal charges pending against them although they may have criminal records, must certify that no insurance company or third party will pay for the cost and must not have been through a drug treatment program before. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said there is a `` considerable waiting list,'' although he said he did not know the number waiting. <PERSON> Chip </PERSON> <PERSON> Burson </PERSON>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> Bradford </LOCATION>, said most patients would stay from 30 to 45 days. After that, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said, they are to receive two years of follow-up treatment in the district, which they agree to pay for through some form of community service. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said the council is negotiating with three treatment groups in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> suburbs that have approached it about similar programs.
