<HEAD>Special Prosecutor Wants Attorney General's Appeal Powers Limited</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The attorney general should not be empowered to appeal a judge's secrecy order in trials being conducted by independent counsels, <ORGANIZATION> Iran-Contra </ORGANIZATION> prosecutor <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, appointed an independent counsel in 1986 to investigate the Iran-Contra affair, urged the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> legislative affairs subcommittee against adopting legislation to specifically give the attorney general such power under the Classified Information Procedures Act. The independent counsel, speaking to reporters after the closed hearing, noted that the attorney general already has the power to file a court affidavit blocking a trial if he feels disclosure of certain secrets in open court would endanger national security. But <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, who was forced to jettison three major conspiracy charges against former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> because of the government's refusal to release certain classified information, said the attorney general should not be allowed to appeal trial-court rulings on secrecy in cases conducted by special prosecutors. To do so would undermine the independence of special prosecutors, said <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>. `` If the attorney general feels that a case should be interrupted to protect classified information, that should be a clean-cut act which the public can understand and for which he takes political responsiblity,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said in an allusion to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s response to secrecy problems arising from his prosecution of a former <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> agent. `` He's not in there to tinker with it. And he should not come in unless he wants to kill the case,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said. In a report to the committee released after the hearing, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> pointedly noted that Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> threatened to file an affidavit preventing disclosure of secrets in the trial of former <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> station chief <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>. As jury selection was set to begin on July 24, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> instead sought a stay of the trial while he appealed the judge's ruling that the details of three <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> programs in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and the locations of <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> stations in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> could be disclosed in court. The 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> is now considering whether the attorney general has right to appeal such a ruling. The appellate court has stayed the trial of <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, accused of lying about his role in setting up a clandestine arms resupply network for the Nicaraguan Contras. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> also urged the panel to adopt legislation requiring the attorney general to notify the intelligence committees of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> so those panels `` would be able to look at the so-called secret information to see whether it's a true secret.'' `` The basic controversy is as to matters which are classified but which are publicly known,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said. `` There are some matters, which even though the public knows it, the intelligence agencies wish to keep classified, and not release even for use at trial, even though it may mean that the trial has to be dropped,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said. Before the trial of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION>, who was convicted of three Iran-Contra coverup charges, intelligence agencies objected to the identification of countries that helped arm the Nicaraguan Contras. Similar secrecy problems have arisen in the <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> case, even though some of the same secrets were disclosed in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION>'s trial. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said that the intelligence agencies are apparently concerned that `` in the framework of the <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> case, it might get into much more nitty-gritty detail.'' `` While I recognize these problems, but to defeat a case ... to protect that rather abstract concern, seems to me going too far,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said. Rep. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> McHugh </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, the subcommittee chairman, said the panel may draft some legislation but first wants to hear testimony from <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, whom he said has refused so far to discuss the issue.
