<HEAD>Victim of Shotgun Rampage Urges Senators: Strengthen Death Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fighting back tears, a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> woman whose jaw was destroyed by a drug user's shotgun a decade ago told senators Tuesday the nation needs strong death penalty laws. `` The problem I see with the death penalty is the lengthy appeals process,'' <PERSON> Wanda </PERSON> <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> of <PERSON> Pawley </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which is considering measures to increase the number of crimes that could result in death sentences under federal law. Senators commended Mrs. <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> for bravery in telling the story of the Feb. 22, 1979, murder spree by two men that left four dead. She and a fellow worker at a convenience store were taken to a deserted road, raped and shotgunned, she testified. Her assailant, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Woomer </PERSON>, left her for dead, Mrs. <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> said. Actually, she turned her head at the moment of the shotgun blast, which blew away part of her mouth and her jaw. Despite her wound, she was able find help, but her co-worker died in the incident. The two assailants were found the same night in a <LOCATION> Myrtle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> motel. One of them, <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Skaar </PERSON>, committed suicide. <PERSON> Woomer </PERSON> was captured, convicted of murder and sentenced to death. He has been on death row ever since as the appeals process has continued. Mrs. <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> said she has been helped by reconstructive surgery and psychiatric care, but added that it `` is hard to get up in the morning and look in the mirror.'' `` It's hard when little kids stare at you and adults try not to. Its hard to smile when you know how you look when you do.'' She was asked by Sen. <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON>