TION>, with the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> likely to feel the hurricane's effects in two to three days. `` Hopefully, we'll be able to narrow that somewhat tomorrow,'' Sheets said. Emergency officials up and down the coast began making plans for the hurricane, although most said it was too early to take any defensive action. `` Right now, we're just watching the storm,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. `` Tomorrow, we'll be having a meeting with the shelter managers, school superintendants and others to review the procedures. In <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON> said all emergency workers had been placed on standby alert and officials were contacting volunteers to make sure they are prepared to help out in a disaster. And in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials fretted about the space shuttle Atlantis, sitting on its pad at <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION> in preparation for an October launch. Space agency officials decided to wait until Wednesday before deciding whether to pull the spacecraft back into the safety of its hangar _ a tedious procedure that could delay its flight. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> ordered food and made last-minute preparations to open 58 shelters in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and 23 in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, and several radio stations in central <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> planned to activate storm trackin