<HEAD>First 25 Movies Named to National Film Registry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with reaction, inserting new 2nd graf and 6 grafs after
10th graf, The registry, and moving up pvs 15th graf bgng, Any film</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday the first 25 American movie classics to be placed on the new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Registry </ORGANIZATION> as `` culturally, historically or esthetically significant'' treasures in the art form of filmmaking. The list was heavy with popular, Academy Award-winning titles, from `` The Best Years of Our Lives'' to `` The Wizard of Oz.'' It included one documentary, `` Nanook of the North'' and one contemporary hit, 1977's `` Star Wars.'' Librarian of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> said the selections do n't constitute a list of the best American movies, but most are easily recognizable among moviegoers' all-time favorites. The 25, listed alphabetically: `` The Best Years of Our Lives,'' 1946; `` Casablanca,'' 1942; `` Citizen Kane,'' 1941; `` The Crowd,'' 1928; `` Dr. <PERSON> Strangelove </PERSON>; or, How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb,'' 1964; `` The General,'' 1927; `` Gone With the Wind,'' 1939; `` The Grapes of Wrath,'' 1940; `` High Noon,'' 1952; `` Intolerance,'' 1916; `` The Learning Tree,'' 1969, and `` The Maltese Falcon,'' 1941. Also, `` Mr. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> Goes to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' 1939; `` Modern Times,'' 1936; `` Nanook of the North,'' 1922; `` On the Waterfront,'' 1954; `` The Searchers,'' 1956; `` Singin' in the Rain,'' 1952; `` Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs,'' 1937; `` Some Like it Hot,'' 1959; `` Star Wars,'' 1977; `` Sunrise,'' 1927; `` <LOCATION> Sunset </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boulevard </LOCATION>,'' 1950; `` Vertigo,'' 1958, and `` The Wizard of Oz,'' 1939. <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> sought to defuse an almost certain controversy among film critics and scholars over the selections. `` Make no mistake, this list of 25 films is not a list of the best 25 American films,'' he said. `` Film critics and scholars could not agree on such a list, and the <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would not embark on any such futile exercise. This is not Academy Awards night.'' Rather, he said, the list `` should suggest to the American public the breadth of great American filmmaking'' under guidelines set by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. No films less than 10 years old were eligible, and there was only one issued in the past 20. The registry was created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year as part of the National Film Preservation Act, which called for naming 25 outstanding movies to the registry at the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> annually for three years. The legislation was prompted partly by the recent boom in coloring of black and white films, a practice loudly protested by moviemakers. The law does not prevent coloring, but any film listed in the National Film Registry must carry a warning label if it has been colorized or `` materially altered'' in versions produced for video cassettes, television broadcast or other showings. Three directors whose films were chosen, <PERSON> Elia </PERSON> <PERSON> Kazan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Donen </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should halt colorization. `` They should take the next step, to protect those films from all kinds of distortion _ speeding up, colorization and all the other things that have been done to them _ and leave them the way we made them,'' <PERSON> Kazan </PERSON> said. `` That is what they can do to really show how they honor our films.'' Seven of the winning films are owned by broadcasting magnate <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, who is a champion of film colorization. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Kehr </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Critics </ORGANIZATION> and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said that the movies chosen made up `` a very safe, conservative list'' but that he wished they `` had been a little more reflective of bread-and-butter Hollywood.'' Each film added to the government's version of a movie hall of fame will bear a seal designating it `` as an enduring part of our national cultural heritage.'' The Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will obtain a high-quality print of the original version of the movie for its collection of more than 75,000 film and television titles dating to the 19th century. <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> said half of all movies made before 1950 and 80 percent of those made before 1930 have been lost forever, because of the deterioration of early nitrate film into powder and because of sloppy cuts and editing of films for videotapes and TV broadcasts. `` The cold, hard fact is that for all their popularity in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> today, films are an endangered species for the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> of tomorrow,'' <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> said. The list is the result of a lengthy process involving nominations of nearly 1,000 movie titles by mail from the general public. The list was narrowed substantially by the 13 members of the new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> which met in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in July. <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> made the final selection of the 25 top films and indicated Tuesday that he personally made at least one addition to the list, which he refused to identify. He said there was no overwhelming, all-time favorite nominated by the public or chosen by the panel of experts. The board included representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Critics </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Screen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Actors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, movie and TV producers and film scholars. <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> said his goals in selecting the outstanding films were to help promote movies as an indigenous <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> art form and generate public interest in preserving films.
