<HEAD>Soviet Immigrant Who Staged Hunger Strike Becomes U.S. Citizen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ceremony lasted only a few minutes Tuesday, but for Soviet immigrant <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON>, the journey to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship took years. Eight years ago, <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> staged a hunger strike for 26 days in his homeland to attract the attention of Soviet authorities, who ignored his plea to join his American wife. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, his wife did the same. After a year of bureaucratic haggling, <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON>'s name was added to the list of Soviet citizens with a spouse in the West who was allowed to leave in 1982. Years later, <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON>, dressed in a three-piece gray suit, stood outside a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> courtroom ready to fulfill his dream of citizenship. `` It's a great day,'' <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> said while waiting for the ceremony. <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> has been working as a translator for a Russian-language newspaper in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> since March, when he left his position at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Language </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION>. He is also translating his play about life in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, `` Strangers Do n't Enter,'' into English, and hopes one day to have it produced. `` I expected life would be hard here because I did not know English well and I could n't use my education here. It's getting better,'' he said. A shy, soft-spoken man, <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> worked as a taxi driver, furniture mover and bookstore clerk before he began teaching Russian to soldiers at the institute in <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION> is a pretty small town, and there is a small community of Russian instructors,'' he said. `` Sometimes it looks like the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. But it is better to be among Americans.'' <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON>, 58, joined 150 others for the naturalization ceremony Tuesday. He stood stiffly, with a stern look on his face. Afterward, he pulled a voter registration form out of his pocket and proudly proclaimed his intention to register _ probably as a Democrat. Asked how he felt, he said simply, `` Great.'' <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON>'s journey began with a fascination with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. A journalist in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, he read American literature and watched movies in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> theaters. Friends teased him, calling him an `` Americaniste.'' Then he met <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON>, an American student working on a dissertation at <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION>. Nine months later, they married. When <PERSON> Becker </PERSON>'s visa expired, she was forced to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> without her husband when she was unable to find work. It was the beginning of the couple's yearlong struggle against what became a bureaucratic nightmare. Then, for reasons that remain unknown, Soviet authorities allowed <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> to leave, and he and <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> were reunited. The transition was not easy; they separated in 1985 and later divorced. <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> worked at a string of subsistence-level jobs after he arrived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He recalls the early days in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, when a trip to the supermarket could overwhelm him. Living alone in a rundown house in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> would rise early to practice English, watch television to further improve his conversational skills, and then set off for work in a bookstore. He studied at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> three nights a week, and would walk the streets at any hour to satisfy his wanderlust. Although his life in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has been filled with challenges, <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> said he has no regrets about leaving the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` I still feel some kind of pain. I do n't want even to visit <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.''
