<SECOND>AM-Film Registry-Reax,0885</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government List of Significant Films Draws Favorable Response</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Film Registry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' list of 25 films deemed `` culturally, historically or esthetically significant'' drew generally favorable reviews Tuesday from <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> and other film industry figures. `` I'm delighted,'' said <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, whose `` Some Like It Hot'' and `` Sunset Boulevard'' are listed. `` I wish things would go forward to reconstruct those films as they were, not colorized and not butchered by cuts.'' `` The first thing that crossed my mind,'' said <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, who starred in the <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Capra </PERSON> film `` Mr. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> Goes to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' also on the list, `` is that I'm glad that <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> is still with us and can enjoy his vindication.'' `` I think it's a terrific list; I'd like to see all of them,'' commented <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirgo </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. `` The only omission I see is ` The Apartment,' but <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> is pretty well represented.'' `` I'm so happy these 25 films have been selected,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiller </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'd be even happier if more films could have been selected, as the -LRB- Congressional -RRB- bill intended. I'd be happiest if there were no need for a bill, and the moral rights of all artists not to have their works altered or defaced would be protected.'' The major surprise among the selections for the new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Registry </ORGANIZATION> was the 1969 `` The Learning Tree,'' a semi-autobiographical film of a black boy's rural childhood by <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Parks </PERSON>, famed Life magazine photographer. `` I'm surprised, pleasantly so,'' said <PERSON> Parks </PERSON> at his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> residence. `` I'm very happy. The film was very well received in its release, and it's still playing in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and on television here.'' The National Film Registry is the outgrowth of protests by filmmakers over the colorization and the editing for television of classic films. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year passed the National Film Preservation Act which called for the naming of 25 classic films annually for three years. `` I'm delighted to be one of the 25, but I'm horrified at the necessity of the act,'' said <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Donen </PERSON>, the director of the musical `` Singin' in the Rain.'' <PERSON> Donen </PERSON> said that the act will do nothing to keep broadcasters from editing movies for length or duplicating them with poor quality control onto videocassettes. The aim, said Librarian of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilington </PERSON> in announcing the first 25 Tuesday, was to help promote movies as an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> art form and generate public interest in preserving films. `` I think it's as good a list as we can expect the first time out,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Kehr </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Critics </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's a very safe, conservative list. ... I wish the list had been a little more reflective of bread and butter Hollywood.'' Said film critic <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Maltin </PERSON>: `` I feel that they've chosen such generally outstanding titles that whatever omissions one could argue this year will be rectified next year if not the year after.'' A board of 13 film figures made the final selection, drawing from a thousand nominations from the public. <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> made his comments in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, between a bookstore signing for his new volume of poetry and a visit to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to campaign for more protection for films. He recalled the premiere of `` Mr. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> Goes to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'' at Constitution Hall in 1939. The invited senators became restive at the film's depiction of political corruption. The film broke during the screening, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> recalled, and by the time <PERSON> Capra </PERSON> returned to his seat after climbing to the projection booth to repair it, `` half his audience was gone. ... The press was completely against the picture, too.'' `` The main thing is that <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> is still here to enjoy his vindication,'' said the actor. <PERSON> Capra </PERSON> has been in failing health at his home in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quinta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> was his usual acerbic self in calling for greater protection for films: `` The television people call in a butcher, who has failed at the <ORGANIZATION> Ralphs </ORGANIZATION> grocery store, to supervise the cutting of pictures so they can slip in the Noxema commercials Frankly, nobody gives a -- --.'' The list of 25 offers some surprises, especially `` The Learning Tree,'' as well as glaring omissions. <PERSON> D.W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON>'s mishmash of history, `` Intolerance,'' was selected, but not his great classic, `` The Birth of a Nation,'' perhaps because of its sympathetic portrayal of the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION>. King <PERSON> Vidor </PERSON>'s `` The Crowd'' was included but not his more impressive achievement, `` The Big Parade.'' <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westerns </ORGANIZATION> are represented by `` The Searchers'' and not his landmark `` Stagecoach.'' Other debatable choices: <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON>'s 1922 documentary, `` Nanook of the North''; <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kubrick </ORGANIZATION>'s 1964 `` Dr. <PERSON> Strangelove </PERSON>''; <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murnau </PERSON>'s 1927 `` Sunrise.'' Among the missing: `` The Treasure of the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madre </LOCATION>''; `` It's a Wonderful Life''; `` It Happened One Night''; `` All about Eve''; `` Shane''; `` Top Hat''; `` The African Queen''; `` Rebecca''; `` From Here to Eternity.'' Besides <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, double selections were <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>, who directed both `` Gone with the Wind'' and `` The Wizard of Oz'' in 1939, and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, `` The Grapes of Wrath'' and `` The Searchers.''
