<FIRST>u w AM-AIDSStudies     09-19 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Studies,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many AIDS Patients Die of Malnutrition, Study Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITS a0764 to add relevant headline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many AIDS patients die as a direct result of simply wasting away because their bodies are unable to retain enough food for adequate nourishment, according to a study released Tuesday by a <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> researcher. `` Improving nutritional status provides a reasonable expectation'' for prolonging life and maintaining the quality of life for AIDS patients, reports Dr. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kotler </PERSON>, an associate professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physicians </ORGANIZATION> and Surgeons and the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lukes-Roosevelt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In a study published in the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kotler </PERSON> estimated that 70 percent to 80 percent of AIDS patients die as a result of wasting away. In studying the process, <PERSON> Kotler </PERSON> uses a measurement called body cell mass _ the weight of muscle and organs, excluding fat, bone and water outside the cells. In a study 32 AIDS patients, patients died when the body-cell mass dropped to an average of 54 percent of the ideal. The study started 100 days before death when the average body-cell mass was 71 percent of the ideal. Body-cell mass gives a more accurate picture of the state of malnutrition because patients can lose body-cell mass while not losing weight dramatically, <PERSON> Kotler </PERSON> said. In a comments at a meeting Tuesday of the <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Societies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Experimental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biology </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kotler </PERSON> said the study did not determine the precise mechanism that causes death due to malnutrition among AIDS patients. `` We do not know whether death is due to a general cellular starvation so that a critical number of cells stop functioning or some critical organ, such as the brain, liver, kidneys or heart, stops functioning,'' he said. Dr. <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Callaway </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> told the meeting that <PERSON> Kotler </PERSON>'s study suggests that a control of malnutrition among AIDS patients might prolong life. `` While we will have to wait on studies to prove that adequate nutrition can prolong life in AIDS patients, from a doctor's point of view, I consider it only responsible to treat patients with the information that we have,'' said <PERSON> Callaway </PERSON>. <PERSON> Callaway </PERSON> said vomiting and diarrhea are the most common causes of malnutrition among AIDS patients, and these symptoms often can be treated with drugs or food selection that will improve nutrition. `` While nutrition does not solve the primary problem, the AIDS viral infection, it can improve the quality of patients' lives,'' he said. `` Many problems that cause malnutirition in AIDS patients are treatable by fairly simple interventions.'' In another report at the meeting, scientists from <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> reported that they cleared all detectable signs of AIDS from a patient through a combination of radiation and chemotherapy to kill the patient's bone marrow cells, AZT to prevent the AIDS virus from invading new cells, and a bone marrow transplant. The patient, a 41-year-old man, died 46 days after the treatment from a type of cancer, but no trace of AIDS genetic material could be detected in tissue samples from the patient. `` Even though the patient died, we believe we demonstrated that he was cleared of all signs of the AIDS virus,'' said Dr. Rein Saral, a <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> associate professor. He cautioned the results should not be interpreted as a `` cure'' for AIDS because the virus could still have been present in some cells of the patient's body.
</TEXT>
