<HEAD>Panel to Recommend 35 Percent Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A special bipartisan <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> task force will present to the leadership this week a call for a congressional pay increase of about 35 percent over two years, a congressional said Tuesday night. Other recommendations would end fees for making speeches and the conversion of campaign funds to personal use. The source, who is in a position to know the recommendations and who spoke on condition of anonymity, cautioned that the entire package of rules changes planned by the task force could be changed before it is proposed to the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which must be done by the end of October. The heart of the package is the pay plan, which would include about a 10 percent raise in 1990 and an additional 25 percent in 1991. After 1991, members would get cost-of-living pay increases. House and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> members currently earn $ 89,500 per year, with leaders earning more. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would have to approve any pay increases, which would apply to both bodies. A 35 percent increase would make the salary $ 120,825. A key part of the plan would phase out honoraria _ fees for making speeches, often to organizations lobbying for legislation _ over two years. Since <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members now can keep honoraria totaling 30 percent of their pay, the 35 percent salary increase would mean no member would lose money by the phase-out. The honoraria system has been much criticized by watchdog organizations such as Common Cause. Critics say the fees, limited to $ 2,000 per occasion, too often amount to a reward just for showing up, sometimes at conventions at plush resorts for which the member's expenses are picked up by the sponsors The plan also would phase out the `` grandfather clause'' under which members who were in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in January 1980 can convert leftover campaign funds to personal use when they retire. The date when the prohibition would take full effect has not been settled, the source said. Other provisions of the package call for tightening requirements to disclose gifts. The ethics panel was appointed by former Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, after lawmakers earlier this year fought a bitter, divisive battle over a proposed 51 percent pay raise that was rejected after a campaign led by consumer advocate <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> and others who argued that it was excessive. The 51 percent proposal came from an advisory commission and was recommended by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. It would have taken effect without a vote unless rejected by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had devised a plan to raise salaries by 30 percent in return for dropping honoraria, but <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members overwhelmingly voted to reject such a plan. Backers of a raise say members have not taken cost-of-living increases in recent years and need a substantial increase to catch up with inflation. Many members feel they must maintain two homes, one in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and one in their districts, and face expenses that others with similar salaries do n't have, the supporters say. The task force of 10 members is equally divided between the parties and chaired by Reps. <PERSON> Vic </PERSON> <PERSON> Fazio </PERSON>, D-Calif., and <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, R-Ill
