<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Taba Resort, Adv 26,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs Sept. 26 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Egypt Now Runs Sinai Beach Resort But Clientele Remains Israeli</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year ago, international arbitration ended the last border dispute between <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, a squabble over a 250-acre strip of beach and the plush hotel on it. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> lost. Now, six months after the Israelis ceded <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, the former <ORGANIZATION> Aviya-Sonesta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> is struggling to develop an Egyptian image while catering to its main clientele, Israelis. `` It's still the same hotel,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON>, the general manager through successive owners and management chains. But, he said, `` instead of a waiter called <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON>, we now have <PERSON> Moussa </PERSON>.'' Opened in 1982 by its builder, the Egyptian-born Israeli <PERSON> Eli </PERSON> <PERSON> Papouchado </PERSON>, the 10-story, 327-room luxury hotel has panoramic views of the Gulf of <LOCATION> Aqaba </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Sinai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>'s rugged mountains. It quickly became a favorite among Israelis whose army seized the Sinai in the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> war of 1967. Although <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> had been in dispute since early 1982 when <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> refused to return it with the rest of Sinai under terms of a 1979 peace agreement, Israelis nonetheless were shocked on Sept. 29, 1988, to find the place no longer belonged to them. After deliberating 18 months, international arbitrators ruled that Egyptian claims prevailed and ordered <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to end its occupation. Months of haggling followed over special facilities for <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> tourists and compensation to owner <PERSON> Papouchado </PERSON> _ the settlement was $ 37 million _ but <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> finally raised its flag over <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> on March 15. Egyptian nationals marched into the hotel, <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION>'s only significant structure, to claim jobs. Outside, Israeli employees burned street barricades of automobile tires and demonstrated to protest their uncertain future. About 280 of the 306 Israeli workers last March have been laid off to comply with <LOCATION> Egyptian </LOCATION> law that limits foreign employment to 10 percent of the work force. But manager <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> said in a telephone interview the hotel staff has become a model of co-existence. `` This is beautiful,'' he said. `` I wish the governments would take an example from the harmony.'' Many details remained unsettled and confusion reigned at the turnover in March, but much of that has dissipated as technical problems have been ironed out. Israelis stayed away in the first weeks after the turnover, and the hotel's occupancy rate fell from better than 90 percent to around 40 percent. <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> said that by August it had recovered much of the lost ground. Hotel shopowners, mostly Israelis, feared working under <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s more stringent import controls, but they've settled into their new state of affairs Prices on menus are being changed gradually to Egyptian pounds from Israeli shekels and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars. <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION>, at the northern tip of the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aqaba </LOCATION>, 230 miles east of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, was a wasteland at the end of a desert wadi when <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured the <LOCATION> Sinai </LOCATION> in the 1967 war. Thus, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> has no infrastructure there to support the hotel and must buy water, electricity and some goods from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION>'s telephone lines are linked through <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> And because there is no housing at <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> other than the hotel, Egyptian employees must travel 90 miles a day to and from <LOCATION> Nuweiba </LOCATION> to go to work. The 28 Israeli employees commute from <LOCATION> Eilat </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> port which is close by. They work in positions where Hebrew is necessary to communicate with patrons. The Egyptian personnel manager, <PERSON> Aly </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Aziz </PERSON>, said Israeli singers and two belly dancers still perform but with fewer Hebrew songs. Although their flag flies over <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> now, Egyptians have n't flocked to the resort One reason may be room rates of $ 150 a night. Few Egyptians can afford even the reduced rate of $ 54, which is high for a country with an average monthly take-home pay of $ 40. But <PERSON> Fuad </PERSON> <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s tourism minister, said plans are under way to promote <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> worldwide as a warm-weather resort and to equip a nearby landing strip for large airplanes. `` Until <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> was returned to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, it was only a satellite of <LOCATION> Eilat </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Now it's our goal to create something that says, ` This is really <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>.'''
</TEXT>
