<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Agents Adv21   09-19 1177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Agents, Adv 21,1206</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Sept. 21, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hollywood's Superagents: Creative Forces or Money Grubbers?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Even in a city where titanic deals are fairly ordinary, the one the <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> talent agency cut for itself on `` The Cosby Show'' was a whopper. For simply introducing <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON> to the show's producers, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> negotiated a contract bringing the agency 10 percent of every dollar `` The Cosby Show'' generates, a windfall in excess of $ 100 million since 1984. The pact dramatizes the power that agencies like <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Creative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> now wield in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, especially through packaging TV shows. With packaging, a longtime practice in the movie industry, agents deliver the key ingredients for a hit movie or TV series. However, packaging also sometimes provides agents with extravagant payments _ usually a percentage of a show's revenues _ for little more than introducing one agency client to a producer. For some, the practice smacks of artistic extortion, and those involved in making deals are reluctant to talk about it. `` It's <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> saying, ` Fellas, you wan na open a bar in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>? This is the deal: My beer. My laundry. My glasses. My bartender. My union. My trucks,''' said a top TV writer-producer who spoke on condition of anonymity. What bothers the production community is that package fees come from the production itself, taking away funds that could help make a better project. And for some producers, paying a package commission can mean the difference between profit and loss. `` I think -LRB- packaging -RRB- is absolutely the worst waste of money that you could possibly imagine,'' said writer-producer <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>, one of the few who would allow his name to be used. `` I think it's an extortion ... and one of the worst abuses in this business.'' <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>, whose credits include the old TV series `` <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>,'' `` Bewitched'' and `` That Girl,'' recently signed a deal with <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to create TV and movie products. At one time, and occasionally today, television packaging represented a real service. A packaged show _ a Perry Como or <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> special, `` The <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON> Show'' _ might have included a writer, a director, a star, other related talent and perhaps even advertisers, bookkeepers and lawyers. The movie business still represents an area in which packagers serve an essential role. For no extra fee _ no package commission _ agents bring together several clients to form an outstanding team. Such was the case with <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> and the cast of `` Platoon,'' and the recent `` Mississippi Burning'' and `` Rain Man.'' Network executives say privately that as much as they despise television packaging, they are reluctant to do anything about it because if one network stops the practice, another network will accept the deals. CBS, however, was so concerned about packaging fees that it held discussions during last year's writers strike to see whether the strike could be settled if packaging fees were abolished. The talks failed to result in any action. Several top producers maintain that the three top agencies _ <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION> and ICM _ sometimes are interested more in negotiating big packaging commissions for themselves than in promoting their clients' careers or making good shows. `` There are a lot of deals that do n't get made that should have because somebody objects to a package commission,'' said one top TV executive. At least one TV executive has asked <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> legislators to address the package issue. But the Department of Industrial Relations, which regulates agents' fee schedules, does not determine package fee limits, said spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>. The top agencies are privately held and declined to be interviewed. <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION> operates with almost comical secrecy. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurtzman </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION>'s business affairs department, would not even decline to be interviewed unless he could do so off the record. Thus, it is hard to pinpoint every packaged show. However, published reports suggest that `` The Cosby Show,'' `` Roseanne,'' `` Golden Girls,'' `` Empty Nest,'' `` Beauty and the Beast'' and `` The Famous Teddy Z'' are just a few of the packaged shows now on the air. The packaged talent in most situation comedies is the writer-producer. But almost anybody can be packaged in a miniseries or movie. The payoffs can be tremendous. <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION>, more than any other agency in town, is rolling in money. To appreciate <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION>'s embarrassment of riches, consider the case of the <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION> ficus tree: I.M. <PERSON> Pei </PERSON>, the famed architect who designed the agency's elaborate new office, selected <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION>'s huge tree from a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> grove and then shipped it to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> for a year's acclimatization The privately held agency, representing more than 600 top clients like <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON>, grossed $ 65 million last year, and <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ovitz </PERSON> himself made $ 10 million, according to the entertainment industry newsletter Show Biz News. By controlling so many leading actors, writers and directors, the superagents can cut deals pretty much on their own terms. Producers not willing to play along often find doors locked. Television and movie executives are convinced that anyone speaking publicly against the superagents will suffer greatly, perhaps kept from signing an agency's top talent. Those few agents who do grant interviews defend packaging, saying it provides a real service, often helping to create a hit show. `` It does n't need justification, because it works,'' said <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON>, a founder of Triad Artists. `` When a network buys a show that's successful, they increase their revenues. ... And you've created that potential for them. <PERSON> Chet </PERSON> <PERSON> Migden </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Talent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agents </ORGANIZATION>, said package deals generate more work for actors, directors and writers. `` In order to get work for clients, agents began to think creatively about putting properties together.'' Without package fees, agents take a percentage commission _ usually 10 percent _ on their clients' paychecks, and no more. With packaging fees, agents charge from 6 percent to 10 percent on the total cost of each and every episode in a TV series. With a normal commission, for example, a writer paid $ 50,000 a week by a situation comedy would give his agent $ 5,000 a week. The packaged clients keep 100 percent of their checks. With a package deal on that sitcom costing $ 700,000 a week, the agent collects up to $ 70,000 weekly, plus up to 10 percent of everything the series makes in the fruitful syndication market. Producers are trapped by the package commission because networks will not buy shows unless they have the top talent usually covered by packages. If one producer refuses to pay a package fee, there is always another who will. `` The agencies are n't fools,'' said one television producer. `` They know if we need these things to make the programs we produce more noticeable ... they can extract a premium for that. `` The networks continue to ask only for the ` A' players. ... And the ` A' players are controlled by fewer and fewer agencies.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs AMs, Sept. 21</NOTE>
