<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Christian Churches Divided Along Racial Lines</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DAVID BRIGGS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 They worked together in the civil rights movement and share a faith that recognizes no racial boundaries, but <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>'s flock in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> remains largely divided into black and white sheep. Gains in integration in business, government and education have not been matched in the church, which some observers say may be the nation's most segregated institution. Why? `` Is n't it obvious? It's racism. That's what brought about the black church since its inception _ slavery _ and it has n't changed,'' said the Rev <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of Christian education for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. More than seven in 10 black Americans say they are Methodists or Baptists, according to a 1988 Gallup Poll Yet, in the nation's largest Protestant denomination, the 14.8 million-member <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, only an estimated 3 percent are black In the 9 million-member <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, an estimated 4 percent of members are <PERSON> black </PERSON>. In the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, a black priest has started his own church in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and the nation's black bishops have condemned racism within the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> church, although the 53 million-member body has more black members _ an estimated 2 million _ than any other predominantly white Christian group. The segregation is even greater in the black churches. `` A fraction of a fraction of 1 percent'' is the estimated number of whites in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, according to <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. Officials in the 3 million-member African <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> estimate one-tenth of 1 percent of its members are white. `` Sunday morning is the most segregated time in the country,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a white Presbyterian pastor who is co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interfaith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> White </PERSON> said there is a profound difference between the teachings of Christianity and the way it adapts to the society around it. `` Religion more often than not serves to bolster our own identities. If we are at heart racist, and I believe at heart both blacks and whites are racist, then we ought not to be surprised that religion bolsters that,'' he said. The attempt by the Rev. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> to form an unauthorized parish for black Catholics in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is full of historical precedent. Introduced to Christianity through slavery, black Americans have for centuries moved away from predominantly white churches into churches they had more control over and felt comfortable in. Once criticized for serving as a barrier to blacks in their efforts to make gains in American society, the black church has enjoyed a resurgence since the late 1960s, when blacks and other ethnic groups began to question the value of assimilation and place greater reliance on institutions that preserved their heritage. `` In predominantly white groups, people of black heritage often feel like they're the invisible man. They're there, but not ever seen,'' said <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>, president of the Board of Bishops of the African <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. Despite the solidarity many within predominantly white churches showed in the civil rights movement of a generation ago, the racism that caused the black church remains today, if in more subtle forms, according to black church leaders. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said black churches address the needs of black Americans, while many predominantly white churches embrace the status quo. For example, he said, `` Southern Baptists are hard-pressed to say anything against apartheid, hunger in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, racism among elected officials.'' Some officials in predominantly white churches contend black churches make exaggerated claims of racism because they are fearful of losing members to churches actively seeking to integrate their pews. The Southern Baptist Convention is on record as condemning apartheid, hunger and racism, said the Rev. <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of that denomination's <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. `` I do not mean to imply we have arrived, for we have not,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` But we are not the old-school racist denomination of a generation ago.'' The black church also is not without its own debates on prejudice. In the African <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, for example, there is only one native bishop in the church's six episcopal districts in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Last year, the church elected three bishops to serve <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> _ all were from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, editor of the <ORGANIZATION> A.M.E. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recorder </ORGANIZATION>, said church officials used to say African blacks were not qualified to be bishops. `` That is no longer true, and that would have been no longer true for decades,'' he said. Still, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said, unlike some white churches, the doors of the black church have always been open. `` We've never had a closed-door policy as white Southern Baptists, southern Methodists, Presbyterians have had. We've been the ones rejected and turned away,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. But officials at the nation's largest churches say there has been some movement toward integration. In the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, which split from northern Baptists in the 1840s because of its defense of slavery, six state conventions have elected black presidents, and among Protestant churches, `` we put more money into the black community than any other denomination today, period,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, the general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religion </ORGANIZATION> and Race of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, said her denomination is giving blacks greater leadership roles. For example, while approximately 4 percent of the church members are black, 10 of the church's 49 active bishops are black. As the estimated number of black Catholics has more than doubled from 900,000 to 2 million in 20 years, the church has established a national Office for Black Catholics. Deacon <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, a black clergyman from <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, recalled his Baptist grandfather telling him, `` Catholicism is the church that's going to take a mule to heaven.'' But he stayed within the church, and eventually sought his vocation there. `` I was searching for something all my life. I love the church. The roots of the church go back to my grandmother and mother,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. When he was deciding whether to become a deacon, what impressed him was that `` there was an openness, a reception, and my status as being black did n't matter.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 24</NOTE>
