<FIRST>r f PM-IndustrialConference     09-19 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Industrial Conference,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Chairman Says Trade Imbalance Caused by ``Attractiveness'' of
Goods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The trade imbalance between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is caused by the difference in `` attractiveness'' of the nations' goods, not price, the chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> told world business executives. `` The answer does not lie in protection for high-tech industries,'' <PERSON> Akio </PERSON> <PERSON> Morita </PERSON> said Monday. `` Protectionism runs counter to free market principles and, with the lack of external competition, would only encourage inefficient industries, which are unable to market their products outside of their protected market. `` The real key to competitiveness,'' he said, `` lies not in trade policy but in such areas as increasing investment, strengthening commercial R & amp; D and above all, increasing the quality and spirit of the labor force.'' <PERSON> Akio </PERSON>, speaking to 500 business leaders from 62 countries attending the International Industrial Conference, said investments in improving industrial competitiveness must be viewed as a long-term proposition. `` Perhaps my most basic message is that both the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations should shift their time horizons,'' he said. `` Investments are needed today that will pay dividends in 10, 20 or 30 years.'' <PERSON> Morita </PERSON> also said `` international trade is now being shaken by emotional politicization of the trade imbalance.'' `` I must say that the politicians and governments around the world are not sufficiently aware of the reality of an ever-developing global-scale economy or a borderless economy,'' he said. `` The borderless economy has developed in such a speed and scale exceeding our foresight and imagination.'' Noting the foreign exchange involving billions of dollars, yen and German marks, he said imports and exports of tangible goods are not the only items that generate big money. Intellectual properties, such as patents, know-how and music, also are valuable, he said. `` In my view, bilateral trade is made up of numerous ` buy and sell' transactions between companies in the two nations. An imbalance is the difference in the sum of these transactions over a given time.'' It is important to Americans and the world economy that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry regain its competitiveness, he said. Later, <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communities </ORGANIZATION>, discussed the effort to remove trade barriers between European Community nations by 1992. <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> said he saw no reason that the deadline for achieving a single market would not be reached, despite difficulties in coming to agreement on the automotive, transportation, energy, and telecommunications industries. `` In those four fields the antagonisms between the nations are very destructive, and the interests of firms and the interests of nations are mixed,'' he said. `` I must spend all my time to convince the 12 governments to fulfill the single market and to not accept exceptions ... because the advantage of a single market is enormous in those sectors.'' <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> provoked nervous laughter among the executives when he responded to a question about whether Europeans would develop different trade policies for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` It depends on the Japanese and the Americans,'' he said. `` For example, when I explain the process of reciprocity to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessmen, they understand. They are very positive about the concept. Unfortunately, when I explain this global concept to Japanese, it is more difficult to have an understanding. `` And frankly, we must be very tough with the negotiations with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' he said, `` because it is very difficult for us, our businesses, our banks, to penetrate the Japanese market.'' The remark drew scattered laughs and light applause from the audience, which included dozens of Japanese _ among them <PERSON> Morita </PERSON>, who chaired the proceedings and introduced <PERSON> Delors </PERSON>. `` Excuse me, but it is a matter of fact,'' <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> said to more nervous laughter. When <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> left the podium, <PERSON> Morita </PERSON> thanked him for his remarks and added, `` I promise you to make Japanese easier to understand.''
</TEXT>
