<FIRST>r f PM-JunkBonds Bjt   09-19 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Junk Bonds, Bjt,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sell-Off in Junk Bonds Could Be Blessing in Disguise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Last week's sharp sell-off in the junk bond market could be a blessing in disguise for the economy by making it more difficult for companies to take on much more of the high-cost debt, some analysts say. By scaring off investors, the plunge in junk bonds could make it nearly impossible for companies to sell new junk issues unless there is a strong likelihood they are able to make payments on it over the long run, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lonski </PERSON>, senior economist for <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` You ca n't continue to leverage forever. There has to be some end to what's taking place, and sooner is better than later,'' <PERSON> Lonski </PERSON> said Monday. Issuers of junk bonds _ are high-interest-rate debt securities often used by companies with poor credit ratings _ must pay high interest rates to attract investors. In recent years, the securities have been widely used for such ventures as mergers and acquisitions. But if the economy sours, issuers could be forced to default, adding to the economy's troubles. Quoted bids for junk bonds stabilized Monday after last week's sell-off, although analysts said trading in the most speculative issues nearly ground to a halt `` People feel it's too late to sell and too early to buy,'' said <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> B. Front, an economist at the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> Stein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Farnham </LOCATION>. A cash crunch at <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> retailing giant, triggered last week's price plunge, carrying down even relatively secure issues. <ORGANIZATION> Olympia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Developments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> conditionally agreed Friday to loan <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> $ 250 million in a deal that was expected to give the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> developer greater influence over <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s management and a greater ownership stake After being carried downward by <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s problems, the higher-grade junk bonds such as <ORGANIZATION> Stone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Container </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Owens-Corning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fiberglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Harcourt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jovanovich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> were quoted as much as -RCB- point higher Monday. A point equals $ 10 on a bond with a face value of $ 1,000. Meanwhile, the bid on one issue of <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> unit was quoted down slightly to 26 cents on the dollar from 27. But with bond owners not willing to offer the issue at less than 35 cents, there was virtually no trading, market participants said. The bid for <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> bonds rose 10 to 55, but was still well below the asking price of 65. Companies that were planning to issue junk bonds in coming weeks might postpone or restructure their offerings because of the sell-off, which pushed up yields and made financing more expensive, <PERSON> Lonski </PERSON> said. If wary investors demand higher and higher interest on junk bonds, companies may be less able to rely on the low-grade securities for financing. They then may either pull back from speculative, riskier ventures or finance them in a less risky way, such as by issuing stock. The economy is approaching the seventh birthday of the longest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peacetime expansion in history. But some economists say it may not last much longer. <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Janeway </PERSON>, in a column in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday, warned that dangerously high levels of inventories are accumulating in autos, housing, retailing and metals. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchan </PERSON>, in a column in Monday's editions of the London-based Financial Times, said the shakeout in junk bonds is the latest phase of a `` rolling liquidation'' that in past years had wrung speculation out of agriculture and the energy markets. `` The secret is to shake out the speculators in batches not, as in the 1920s, all together,'' <PERSON> Buchan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, publisher of <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'s Interest Rate Observer, said he believed <PERSON> Buchan </PERSON>'s assessment seemed on target. `` It's always good news when false values are exposed for being false,'' he said in an interview.
</TEXT>
