<SECOND>BC-Birmingham Steel,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harbert Offers $385 Million for Birmingham Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Harbert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday offered about $ 385 million for <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>, a 5-year-old company that prospered by buying older, often financially troubled steel mills at bargain prices. <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> said the decision to sell the company to Birmingham-based <PERSON> Harbert </PERSON> stemmed in part from a desire to keep its headquarters in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>. `` We have had a number of people express an interest in buying out the company,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Harbert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> offered $ 30 a share in cash, or a total of about $ 385 million for the company's stock. <PERSON> Harbert </PERSON>, an international construction company, also would assume and refinance more than $ 100 million in <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> debt. The company's stock closed Monday at $ 29.12 -LCB-, up $ 4.50, in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> had a profit of about $ 39 million in its latest fiscal year on sales of more than $ 343 million. <ORGANIZATION> Harbert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> was founded by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harbert </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, a major <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> investor. A special committee of outside directors, formed by the company to study a possible sale, recommended the <PERSON> Harbert </PERSON> offer after determining there was little room for the stock's price to move above the low $ 20s. The price has been depressed because of <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>'s 50 percent investment in redevelopment of a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, rolling mill, which eventually will make flat-rolled sheet steel. <PERSON> Harbert </PERSON>, chairman of the company, said <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>'s success and strong management team prompted him to make the offer. He already owns less than 5 percent of the company's stock and sits on its board of directors. `` We are knowledgable about this industry,'' he said. The offer must be approved by <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> stockholders.
