<HEAD>Hertz Ends Participation In Airline Frequent-Flier Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it is pulling out of airline frequent-flier programs because the growth of mileage awards had made them too costly for the company. Other national car-rental concerns indicated they might follow the industry leader. But analysts said Monday that while the withdrawal of car-rental companies would make frequent-flier programs less attractive, it did not mean their demise. `` Anytime some feature of the program is eliminated it is less potent as a marketing tool,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Longman </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` But these programs are here to stay. They will just evolve a bit more.'' <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest car-rental company, said the rate of growth of mileage points had doubled in each of the last two years. The value of the redeemed credits last year exceeded $ 15 million, said <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Rigby </PERSON>. `` The program has become very expensive to participate in,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rigby </PERSON> said. `` Double and triple mileage programs have become increasingly common in the last couple of years so the frequency of the awards has grown.'' Ms. <PERSON> Rigby </PERSON> said that because 60 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> customers are business travelers, <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> feels it is giving incentives to people who likely would rent from the company anyway. <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said it would end its participation with <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L