iously they're expensive,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Avis </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Demetria </PERSON> <PERSON> Mudar </PERSON>. `` This sheds a different light on things _ an industry leader making a major move.'' <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Car </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said it also may have an announcement soon on its frequent-flier participation. `` We're taking a hard look at the <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> move,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olsen </PERSON>, spokesman for National Car Rental. <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Car </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said it is not currently considering dropping its frequent-flier partnerships. `` The frequent-flier program is very costly and by itself is not worth the cost,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Smircich </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. `` But the airlines that we are participating with have been good to work for and our participation is not limited strictly to giving out mileage.''
