<HEAD>S&amp;L Industry Still Largest Originator of Home Mortgages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite the savings and loan crisis, the thrift industry continues to be the largest originator of home mortgages, a government study reported. Thrifts retain the lead with 43 percent of single family mortgages and 46 percent of multifamily mortgages, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thrift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervision </ORGANIZATION> study released Monday. Part of the thrift industry crisis was blamed on some savings and loans that engaged in risky investments such as speculative commercial real estate projects and junk bonds rather than home mortgages. The recently enacted savings and loan law, which authorized spending $ 50 billion to bail out the industry, requires thrifts to raise the level of housing and housing-related loans in their portfolios to 70 percent from the current 60 percent. S & amp; Ls have five years to phase out their risky ventures. Savings and loan companies were estimated to have held nearly $ 780 billion in mortgages at the end of 1988, 36 percent of the $ 2 trillion home mortgage market and only 4 percent less than their 1970 share, the study said.
