<HEAD>Company to Upgrade Emission Systems, Fix Seat Belts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says it is recalling nearly 493,000 Escorts and <ORGANIZATION> Mercury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynxes </ORGANIZATION> to fix faulty emission-control systems and 67,156 Tracers because of an apparent seat-belt defect. Repairs of either problem will be made at no charge regardless of a vehicle's age or mileage, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Monday in separate statements. The vehicles recalled for emission-system improvements have 1.9-liter engines and include the 1985 Ford Escort and Mercury Lynx and the 1986 Escort, Lynx and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> EXP </ORGANIZATION>. Excessive emissions of hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide were discovered during routine EPA tests of 1985 models, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. `` We're constantly checking various classes of vehicle to see if a few years after leaving the assembly line, they're still meeting standards,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> did n't request the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> recall but `` we sort of term these recalls EPA-influenced,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Parris </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> attributed the problem to normal wear. `` A few years back, the equipment was not as good as it was now,'' <PERSON> Parris </PERSON> said. `` Some of the valves and small hoses and pieces are starting to wear out and we're having to replace them with upgraded pieces.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> repairs will involve changing the choke system, distributor spark advance and the air-injection system, a pollution-control system that helps the catalytic converter control hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide. Dealers also will install more durable crankcase ventilation valves, also known as PCV valves, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. Cars made for sale in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> are excluded from the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> recall because they are manufactured to meet that state's emission standards, which are more stringent than <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s, <PERSON> Parris </PERSON> said. No <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> cars have been found to fall short of the federal standards, <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. The Tracers being recalled were made in the 1988 model year. There are 66,314 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 842 in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said. In some cases, it has become difficult to extend the front-seat lap-shoulder belts for buckling unless they are pulled very slowly, the company said. A few of the belts may lock and be impossible to pull out. Owners having trouble extending the belts are asked to return the car to the dealer for inspection and repairs if necessary, the automaker said.
