<HEAD>Macmillan Agrees to Buy Merrill Publishing for $260 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the publishing giant controlled by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, has agreed to buy the textbook concern <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> for $ 260 million in cash. The deal would swell <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s share of the educational publishing market, while enabling <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON>'s owner, the privately-held <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Howell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, to make a graceful retreat from that fiercely competitive business. <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, publishes textbooks, software and other learning materials for the elementary, high school and college markets, and officials said it was expected to post more than $ 100 million in revenue this year. The company, founded in 1842, has been owned since 1967 by <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, which is based in <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Herb </PERSON>, vice president-administration at <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, said his company decided to sell <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> for strategic reasons He said consolidation in the educational publishing field put <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> at a competitive disadvantage with larger companies. He said <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> considered making some acquisitions in this field but found few potential candidates and decided several months ago to sell <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION>. The deal is subject to regulatory approval. `` We are extremely pleased to acquire this excellent publisher,'' <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> was quoted as saying in a two-sentence announcement of the deal. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> had told shareholders of <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC last week at their annual meeting in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> that the company was negotiating for a medium-sized educational publishing business in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> was acquired in May 1988 for $ 640 million by a group led by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> and including senior management. Before that deal was completed, <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> had indicated he was interested in pursuing <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> but never made a formal offer. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> subsequently paid $ 2.5 billion for <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION>, which is a leading educational publisher and has a growing information services business. Earlier this year, <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> combined its elementary, secondary and vocational education publishing businesses with those of <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in a 50-50 joint venture called the <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan-McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGAN