<HEAD>Questar Joins Canadian, Swiss Firms in Marketing Refueling Device</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Questar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has joined with Canadian and Swiss firms to market a device that allows natural gas-powered vehicles to be refueled at home and other places where natural gas is available. B.C. Gas of <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sulzer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Winterthur </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Questar </ORGANIZATION> have formed <ORGANIZATION> FuelMaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to develop, make and market the device, <ORGANIZATION> Questar </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday. The new company will be based in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> with offices in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. The compressor developed by <ORGANIZATION> Sulzer </ORGANIZATION> engineers connects directly to the natural gas supply at a customer's home or business. A small-diameter hose with a quick-disconnect coupling is used as the gas is boosted to the 3,000 pounds per square inch pressure needed to fill vehicles' natural gas fuel cylinders. Refueling can be done in about five hours, while the car is unattended, <ORGANIZATION> Questar </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The growing national and international interest in protecting the environment is creating a lot of interest in natural gas as a clean alternative to gasoline,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Benefield </PERSON>, FuelMaker general manager. <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Questar </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary that provides natural gas service in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and southwestern <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, is converting 100 of its service vehicles to natural gas. It recently opened its second natural gas filling station. FuelMaker plans to market the device through natural gas distrubiton utilities. `` We now have a backlog of orders for the first production series and are very enthusiastic about the prospects for FuelMaker,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON>, FuelMaker marketing manager.
