<HEAD>Brazil Said Seeking 90-Day Extension on Foreign Debt Servicing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> plans to ask the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> for a 90-day extension on payments to service its $ 110 billion debt because it can not meet its obligations, a high-ranking official of the country's central bank was quoted as saying. The Mexican government news agency quoted <PERSON> Wadico </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucchi </PERSON>, a governor of the Brazilian <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, as saying President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>'s administration is seeking to gain time in order to receive a $ 600 loan still pending from the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> which will be used to service the debt. <PERSON> Bucchi </PERSON> said the loan is part of a credit-line the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> extended last year but which <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has not received yet. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> can not pay its creditors until it gets it. <PERSON> Bucchi </PERSON> was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> Notimex </ORGANIZATION> as saying he is sure the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> will grant the 90-day extension when he meets Friday with officials of that organization in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is certain the great majority of creditor banks will respond positively to its petition,'' <PERSON> Bucchi </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Notimex </ORGANIZATION> said that <PERSON> Bucchi </PERSON> spoke with reporters in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> resort of <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, where the heads of central banks from <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> began meeting to discuss international strategies to deal with the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> alone owes an estimated $ 104 trillion, and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has the biggest foreign debt in the Third World followed by <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> with $ 107.4 billion. The meeting began in a climate of tension caused by rumors that <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> may declare a moratorium on $ 1.6 billion in interest payments that came due last Friday. However, <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Amaral </PERSON>, adviser on international relations in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, said those reports were wrong. `` It's not true,'' <PERSON> Amaral </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview. `` We are going to look for a solution quickly to reach an agreement with banks.'' <PERSON> Amaral </PERSON> would not elaborate on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s plans. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has previously suspended payments and, according to news reports in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, such a moratorium would help the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> giant maintain its reserves of $ 6 billion but would hurt its chances of obtaining fresh money from international lenders. `` It is our own political economic mistakes that have determined that development in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is lagging behind the rest of the world,'' said <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mancera </PERSON> <PERSON> Aguayo </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s central bank at the opening of Monday's meetings. <PERSON> Mancera </PERSON> said that business activity increased 50 percent over the past 10 years in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, but has not kept pace with industrial nations `` because the powerful nations have closed their markets and paid less for prime materials they import,'' according to the independent Excelsior news agency. He said Latin American nations should find their own solutions and not wait for outside answers `` because there have been failures in the management of the political economy that have aggravated the problems.''
