<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it expects a huge loss after a restructuring that includes the addition of $ 950 million to its loan-loss reserves, a new-stock issue and the sale of 60 percent of its <ORGANIZATION> CIT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> financial services unit to <ORGANIZATION> Dai-Ichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kangyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. But the bank holding company, which made the announcement late Monday, said its plan should significantly improve its capital and reserve position. `` We view this as a very positive endeavor for Manufacturers Hanover,'' Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGillicuddy </PERSON> told reporters at a news conference. Manufacturers Hanover, the nation's seventh largest bank, estimated it would suffer a loss of about $ 775 million for the third quarter and $ 475 million for all of 1989. For the first six months of this year <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION>'s profit was down 62 pecent to $ 209 million, or $ 3.70 a share, from the year-earlier period The 1988 period included about $ 388 million in one-time gains from divestitures and tax benefits. Manufacturers Hanover said <PERSON> Dai-Ichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kangyo </PERSON>, the world's largest bank with assets of $ 410 billion, agreed to pay $ 1.28 billion for the 60 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> CIT </ORGANIZATION>. The transaction is the largest purchase of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company by a Japanese bank. <PERSON> Yuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Oana </PERSON>, a senior managing director of <ORGANIZATION> Dai-Ichi </ORGANIZATION>, said today that the investment in <ORGANIZATION> CIT </ORGANIZATION> allows his bank to offer more services globally and to expand its custom