<HEAD>Koop Denounces Efforts to Export Cigarettes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing throughout with Koop testimony. Also on
general news wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> today denounced efforts to export <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarettes as `` the height of hypocrisy.'' <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>, who is retiring Oct. 1, testified at a hearing of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative against a request by the cigarette industry for government intervention to force <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> to allow sales and advertising of American cigarettes. `` When we are persuading foreign governments to stop the flow of cocaine, it is the height of hypocrisy to export tobacco,'' said <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>, who has conducted a vigorous anti-smoking campaign throughout his tenure. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cigarette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Export </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has requested the intervention and the trade representative is to decide the issue by next May. In 1988, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tobacco exports contributed a record $ 3.5 billion to helping reduce `` this country's onerous trade deficit,'' said export association President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` People throughout <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> will continue to buy and smoke billions of cigarettes each year with or without <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presence in the marketplace,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tallon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION> `` The real issue is whether <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> companies will be allowed to compete, or if the playing field will be abandoned to other foreign manufacturers and local monopolies.'' But Rep. <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON>, D-Mass., said the real issue `` is about the American government using leverage and tax dollars to coerce countries into allowing marketing practices that were outlawed long ago'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> The petition seeks to force <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> `` to overturn a policy of banning cigarette advertisements'' in print and broadcast media, <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. The export association represents three major cigarette companies, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and <PERSON> R.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>. Since 1986, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> have opened markets to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarette brands after being accused of unfair trade and threatened with retaliation against their products. `` I believe that most Americans would be appalled to learn that their government, which banned cigarette advertisements on TV, required warning labels on cigarettes ... is aggressively pushing cigarette addiction overseas through the trade representative,'' <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. `` It is simply inexcusable for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> to exert its great influence to force <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> to reverse its health policy,'' he said. <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> is sponsoring legislation to require that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarette brands sold abroad carry warnings and advertising restrictions equivalent to those in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The industry argues that foreign countries are competent to make their own regulations.
