<FIRST>u f AM-HousingStarts     09-19 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Starts,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Down in August</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inflation Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Housing construction, depressed by a spike in mortgage rates, fell by 5 percent in August, the government said Tuesday in a report many analysts viewed as only a temporary setback for the housing industry. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said new homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.35 million units last month, down from 1.42 million units in July. It was the first decline since May and the largest setback since a 12.7 percent fall last February. Housing starts had risen 1.3 percent in July and 7.5 percent in June. Fixed mortgage rates, which peaked at 11.22 percent in March, had fallen to 9.68 percent by Aug. 4, but then rose by about one-half percentage point through August. However, in recent weeks they have begun edging down slightly, now standing at 10.05 percent, according to the weekly survey by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Economists predicted continued small declines in mortgage rates for the rest of the year and said this should bolster sales and construction figures `` The -LRB- August -RRB- housing starts numbers show builders were waiting out the recent uptick in interest rates,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION>. `` However, the higher rate of building permits is a good sign that the stalled activity in August is only temporary.'' Overall applications for building permits, considered a good barometer of future activity, rose 3.5 percent after falling 2.1 percent in July. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Seiders </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION>, said the drop in construction and another report Tuesday showing consumer prices did not rise in August should convince the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to stop fighting inflation and resume lowering interest rates to bolster the economy. However, other economists said they doubted that the weak construction number would prompt action on the part of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, given the fact that other statistics show the economy is continuing to grow at a healthy rate. `` I do n't think the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will do anything to change policy for the next several months,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Berson </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Peach </PERSON>, senior economist at the <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said he believed that interest rates will fall despite <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> intervention as financial market fears about inflation ease. Construction starts fell earlier this year for four straight months before rebounding in June, the longest string of declines since activity slowed for five months in a row from February through June 1987. The May level of 1.31 million starts was the slowest pace since the 1.30 million rate in December 1982. Total housing starts during the first eight months of the year are down 4.7 percent from the same period of 1988. Construction of single-family homes last month fell 2.5 percent to an annual rate of 1 million units. Single-family starts had risen 5.9 percent in July after falling 0.5 percent in June. Apartment construction fell 11.4 percent in August to an annual rate of 350,000 units. It had fallen 9 percent in July after rising 31.1 percent in June.
</TEXT>
