<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it would make 20,000 experts available worldwide to help its customers adapt to the coming era of software engineering. The statement came as <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> announced, as expected, that it was committing itself to computer-aided software engineering, or CASE. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s endorsement is expected to give a large boost to the high-tech field, which already garners about $ 300 million in annual revenue. Software engineering is intended to replace disorganized methods of software-writing that have led to chaotic, unmanageable and failure-prone programs for large computers. Consultants said <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s promise of experts to help customers was an important part of the announcement, since the transition to software engineering promises to be a real test of programmers' flexibility `` The limiting factor on the introduction of CASE technology is the ability of information systems shops to cope with a radically new culture. It is going to take them quite some years,'' said <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Reston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` It's going to require an investment, not just of the company's time but of a person's ability to recycle themselves, re-engineer themselves,'' said <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Welsh </PERSON>, the Dallas-based director of information systems consulting markets for <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Young </PERSON> Some of the 20,000 experts will come from <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and some from four outside firms designated by <ORGANIZ