<SECOND>AM-Disney-Taxes,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney Suing Over Tax Bill: $12,000 or $1.4 Million?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is challenging a 254 percent property tax increase county officials say was levied to help pay for huge commercial growth and traffic problems near the tourist attraction. Disney on Monday paid <LOCATION> Osceola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> $ 12,000, the company's own estimate of 1989 property taxes owed. The county plans to bill Disney for $ 1.4 million. Disney spokesman <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON> said Tuesday the company filed a lawsuit in state circuit court `` to protect our rights to challenge, although we hope to come to an agreement with county authorities on the whole subject.'' Osceola removed the agricultural classification on most of <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s undeveloped property in the county and jacked up the tax bill to $ 1.4 million. Disney's theme park is located north of the area, in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Disney filed the lawsuit Friday to beat a Monday deadline on challenges to tax assessments. A Disney representative on Monday dropped off checks totaling $ 12,012 _ the company's `` good-faith estimate'' of its 1989 taxes. `` It's kind of like they're thumbing their nose at us, is n't it? Osceola Property Appraiser <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> said. `` I mean $ 12,000 vs. $ 1.4 million. There's a big difference there, would n't you say?'' Until this year, much of <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s 7,013 acres of undeveloped property was classified as agricultural because <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> leased a portion to a cattle rancher and contracted with a timber company to harvest pine trees. The property was assessed at $ 26.9 million last year, and the company paid <LOCATION> Osceola </LOCATION> $ 395,000 in taxes. After removing the agricultural exemption, Day in July reassessed the land at $ 84 million. Disney contends even last year's taxes were excessive because the 1988 payment was based on a commercial classification for part of the property, as well as on the portion classified agricultural. Disney's estimated payment Monday represents the total amount of 1989 taxes the company believes it owes because `` all of that land rightfully should be classified as agricultural,'' <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON> said. `` Under the law, you pay what you feel you should properly pay,'' he said. By contrast, <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> paid its other host county, <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION>, $ 24 million in taxes last year and is expected to pay $ 33.65 million this year. Much of the company's <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> property contain's its prosperous tourist attractions. In recent years, <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> has built the Disney-MGM Studios park, <LOCATION> Pleasure </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and Typhoon Lagoon next in Orange near the Osceola land. But Osceola Commissioner <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Whaley </PERSON> said: `` We have just as many problems from <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> as <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> does. And they're getting $ 33 million in taxes.'' Osceola in 1973 tried to strip Disney of its agricultural classification but <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> won a legal battle. But the tourist attraction has grown since then, county officials argue, and have had a greater impact on the county.
