<HEAD>Ford Purchasing Up to 15 Percent of Jaguar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced plans Tuesday to buy up to 15 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, saying it wanted a long-term relationship with the unprofitable British luxury auto maker. <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION>, which has been battered by flagging sales in its principal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market during the past year, maintained that it wanted to remain independent but did n't rule out collaborating with another car company. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, which already has a huge European presence and is negotiating a possible transaction with Swedish automaker <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>, could benefit from an association with the well-known <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> luxury car line, analysts said. <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> stock soared 97 cents to close at $ 7.33 a share on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, as some speculated that other companies also might be assembling stakes in <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION>'s articles of association limit individual shareholdings to 15 percent until the end of 1990, and the government has veto power over any takeover through the same period. `` It has always been our desire to maintain our independence,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, who was n't identified in keeping with company policy. However, the spokesman also said <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> has held out the possibility of collaborating with another car maker. The spokesman said the Coventry-based company was notified of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s plans on Tuesday and that <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> would n't make any final comment until its board of directors had a chance to discuss them at an unspecified date. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lindsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Halstead </PERSON>, speaking at a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> news conference, said his company's intentions are not hostile. He characterized contact with <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> Chairman Sir <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> on Tuesday as `` friendly and open and we agreed to leave the lines of communication open.'' The two companies held private, informal talks last year which failed to produce any sort of working agreement, <PERSON> Halstead </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has informed the British government of its plans but has not gotten a reaction from <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> officials, said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>. The spokesman said: `` It is too early to say what might happen then -LRB- 1990 -RRB-, but we regard the acquisition of a minority shareholding in <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> as a basis for a longer-term strategic association between our two companies as we explained to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> in private discussion.'' <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> also said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> respected <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION>'s distinctive British character and would want to maintain its separate identity and help strengthen its image. Last Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> posted an after-tax loss of $ 1.7 million on sales of $ 870 million for the first six months of the year. The company expects to sell 20,000 cars in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this year, down from 20,700 in 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which is headquartered in <LOCATION> Brentwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, makes 1.8 million vehicles a year. It has 21 European plants, 11 of them in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, and employs more than110 ,000 people Parent <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is the second largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker behind <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> posted an industry record profit of $ 5.3 billion, or $ 10.96 a share, on revenue of $ 92.45 billion in 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> confirmed earlier this month that it was negotiating with <ORGANIZATION> Saab-Scania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION>, the Swedish airplane, truck and automaker, over a possible transaction. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON>, automotive analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> may have made its move now because it believed <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION>'s share price was headed higher, or because it wanted to preempt a move by another auto maker. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackwood </PERSON>, an automotive analyst at the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Hoare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Govett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, said he would not be surprised if other automakers also were buying <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> stakes. Although <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> is losing money, its brand name is highly valuable, the analysts said. <PERSON> Halstead </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> could benefit from <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s European production and marketing. <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> could benefit from economies of scale in parts and materials purchasing, a