<HEAD>ZZZZ Best Official Ordered to Repay Profits, Gets Triple Penalties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> official was ordered to return profits he made by trading stock in the rug-shampooing firm founded by <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, who was convicted of defrauding investors in a company-wide scam. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Polevoi </PERSON>, 41, of <LOCATION> Simi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> also was ordered Monday to pay $ 675,000 in civil penalties by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelleher </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kelleher </PERSON> told <PERSON> Polevoi </PERSON> to refrain from violating securities laws, the same order he issued last month to <PERSON> Polevoi </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON>, who also was involved in the ZZZZ Best scam. The brothers had ordered 54,200 shares of <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> stock `` sold short'' _ a way of betting a stock price will decline _ in mid-1987, when they knew <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>'s scams were falling apart but before the public had a chance to know, prosecutors said. The brothers jointly were ordered to repay $ 224,860.75 in profits. Each also must pay triple that amount in civil penalties, or $ 674.582.25, according to <PERSON> Kelleher </PERSON>'s order. They already are serving 18-month prison terms for stock fraud and tax fraud for their role in the ZZZZ Best scandal, which used a `` Ponzi scheme'' style scam in which money from later investors was used to pay early debts while nearly no work was actually performed by the company. <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, who started ZZZZ Best as a teen-ager in his parents' garage, was convicted of 57 counts of fraud, conspiracy and other charges, and sentenced to 25 years in prison and ordered to pay $ 26 million in restitution and penalties
