<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures prices declined Tuesday in trading dominated by technical factors. The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, fell 32 cents to settle at $ 19.56 a 42-gallon barrel after having dropped 8 cents on Monday. Among refined products traded on the exchange, the October contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline dropped 0.46 cent to close at 57.67 cents a gallon after picking up 0.52 cent the previous session. Home heating oil for October delivery, which declined 0.23 cent on Monday, lost another 0.77 cent to 54.95 cents a gallon. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, assistant director of the energy group at <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said some of the declines were due to profit-taking as traders took advantage of the market's recent rally. `` We've been in an advancing market and needed to sell off to relieve the overbought condition,'' <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON> said. There were spates of buying during the day, but prices were unable to hold at higher levels, <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON> said. The October West Texas Intermediate contract traded as high as $ 19.80 during the session before dropping back. Oil traders have become cautious in advance of Saturday's meeting of the strategy and price-monitoring committee of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. The eight-member committee, which is expected to discuss <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s overproduction problems, can not make any changes in the cartel's policies but can make recommendations to the full 13-nation Many analysts say market prices could weaken significantly if <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> fails to show at this weekend's meeting that it plans to act decisively to contain overproduction.
