<HEAD>New Veto Fight Looming Over Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to note committee accepts amount but demands
other provisions; PICKS UP 3rd graf, ``Labor Secretary,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Comittee </ORGANIZATION> bowed Tuesday to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s rejection of anything more than a $ 4.25 minimum wage. But it coupled the 90-cent increase in the present $ 3.35-an-hour wage floor with restrictions on the 80 percent subminimum `` training wage'' that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is demanding _ a move that administration officials say will prompt another veto. On a party-line voice vote, the committee approved a bill identical to a measure <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> vetoed in June except that it provides two hourly increases _ one this January and the other in January 1991 _ of 45 cents each. The vetoed bill had provided for three annual increases to $ 4.55 an hour by Oct. 1, 1991. Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> reiterated in a memo <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s promise to veto any bill which raises the current $ 3.35 floor to $ 4.25 in less than three years or that establishes a subminimum `` training wage'' only for first-time job market entrants <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would allow employers to pay an 80 percent subminimum to any newly hired workers. The committee's chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, D-Calif., said the reduction from the previous $ 4.55 wage floor that had been sought was aimed at garnering support from Southern Democrats and some Republicans for an override of another <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> veto While both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last year approved the $ 4.55 minimum wage with a 60-day subminimum training wage applicable only to first-time workers, neither could muster the two-thirds majority needed to override <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s veto. `` There are some Republican members ready to change their votes if the president does n't'' show a willingness to compromise, <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sources said the bill could be brought up there within the next three weeks. Just before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> recessed in August, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> reapproved the same $ 4.55 minimum wage bill that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> vetoed, but with the understanding that it would likely be modified on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has demanded a six-month training wage compared to the 60-day subfloor Democrats are willing to allow. Both sides have indicated a willingness to negotiate away differences in the time span, but neither is budging on the applicability. Rep. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, D-Pa., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel's labor standards subcommittee, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal would allow employers to pay a $ 3.40 subminimum wage perpetually by rotating new hires in and out every 60 days to six months `` I must say to the president, ` Read my lips,''' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said, adopting <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign motto on higher taxes. `` No way will I permit that man to sign a fake increase in the minimum wage for some political purpose two years down the road.''
</TEXT>
