<HEAD>Chances of Market Crash One-in-Four, Experts Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chances of another stock market crash in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the next two years are about one-in-four, according to a poll of investment decision-makers released Tuesday. The poll, conducted by the Wall Street firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, found a higher expectation of a crash now than in similar surveys conducted in February and last October. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> surveyed 232 people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> who make investment decisions for institutions. They included chief investment officers and corporate financial officers at big companies, institutional portfolio managers for stocks and bonds, securities industry analysts and economists. On the average, the respondents saw a 26.6 percent chance of a crash in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> within two years. They also believe there is a 39.5 percent chance of a stock market slide in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in that period and a 23.9 percent probability of one occurring in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. That compares with average probabilities of 23.9 percent for a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crash in a <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> poll taken last February, 42.7 percent for one in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and 26.4 for one in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In October 1988, one year after the crash that rattled both Wall Street and world markets, the same survey found an average 22.8 percent chance for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 42.3 percent for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and 23.7 percent for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> said.
